<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANTS (THE PLAINTIFFS) APPEAL</BOLD> to the Ontario Superior Court of Justice, Divisional Court from the appeal decision of The Honourable Justice N. Jane Wilson dated the 4<SUP>th</SUP> day of April, 2018, made at Toronto, Ontario.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANTS ASK</BOLD> that the appeal decision of The Honourable Justice N. Jane Wilson be overturned, and the decision of Master Donald E. Short, dated August 25, 2017, be overturned, as follows:</P>
<P>1. The Respondent's (Defendant's) cross-motion is dismissed, where the Court <UNDER>cannot</UNDER> order separate hearings on the issues of liability and damages, where the Plaintiffs do not consent to bifurcate the trial;</P>
<P>2. Costs of the appeal; and</P>
<P>3. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court may deem just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS OF APPEAL</BOLD> are as follows:</P>
<P>1. The Honourable Justice N. Jane Wilson:
<P1>a. Erred in law in her interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> to find that the Court could order separate hearings on the issues of liability and damages, where the Appellants (Plaintiffs) do not consent to bifurcate the trial;</P1>
<P1>b. Erred in law in her interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> to find that the Rule limited the Court's jurisdiction to bifurcate <UNDER>jury trials only</UNDER>, despite the fact that the plain reading of the Rule informs that it applies to all trials;</P1>
<P1>c. Erred in law in finding that Master Donald E. Short was not bound by the finding of this Honourable Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael, et al v Potrebic et al.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3655</CITE></CASEREF>;</P1>
<P1>d. Erred in relying heavily on the Supreme Court of Canada decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Carter v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>[2015] 1 SCR 331</CITE></CASEREF>, despite the fact that the case was not before the Court and neither party was given the opportunity to make submissions on it; and she,</P1>
<P1>e. Erred in upholding Master Donald E. Short's conclusion that the Defendant had satisfied the high threshold to justify bifurcation in this case, despite concluding that bifurcation is appropriate only in the most exceptional cases.</P1></P>
<P>2. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:</BOLD></P>
<P>1. Clause 19 (1)(b) of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>;</P>
<P>2. Rule 61 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>; and,</P>
<P>3. Leave to appeal to the Ontario Superior Court of Justice, Divisional Court granting leave to appeal, dated October 11, 2018.</P>
<P><BOLD>October 19, 2018</BOLD></P>
