<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE APPELLANTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>PART I&mdash;HISTORY OF PROCEEDINGS</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. This appeal concerns the right of an infant plaintiff and his mother to have the entirety of their trial heard in a single procedure.</P>
<P>2. This action arises out of a incident on September 12, 2010 in which the Plaintiff, [G.D.] [G.D.] then only four years old, opened a defective sliding balcony door of a rental unit owned by the Defendant, climbed up over a balcony railing, and fell 10&ndash;15 feet to the ground below. As a result of this fall, [G.D.] suffered an undisplaced skull fracture and a closed head injury. This head injury has developed into a number of psychological, behavioural and developmental issues, but the full extent of the brain injury sequelae is unclear.</P>
<P>3. The Plaintiffs brought a motion for extension of time to set the within action down for trial from March 21, 2017 to March 21, 2020. The Defendant brought a cross-motion seeking an order bifurcating the trial on the issues of liability and damages, pursuant to Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. Both parties opposed each other's motions, returnable May 8, 2017.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <BOLD>Decision of Master Short</BOLD>, Appellants' Appeal Book and Compendium, at Tab 7.</P1></P>
<P>4. Master Donald E. Short granted each parties' order in his reasons of August 25, 2017.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <BOLD>Decision of Master Short</BOLD>, Appellants' Appeal Book and Compendium, at Tab 7.</P1></P>
<P>5. The Plaintiffs appealed the Order of Master Short. The appeal hearing was heard by Honourable Justice N. Janet Wilson on February 26, 2018. Justice Wilson released her decision on April 4, 2018. She denied the Plaintiffs' appeal but stated that the case law interpreting Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> was inconsistent and confusing. She advised that there was a need for clarification by appellate authority.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <BOLD>Decision of Justice Wilson</BOLD>, Appellants' Appeal Book and Compendium, at Tab 5.</P1></P>
<P>6. The Plaintiffs sought leave to appeal Justice Wilson's decision to the Divisional Court. On October 11, 2018 leave was granted.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <BOLD>Order Granting Leave to Appeal to the Divisional Court</BOLD>, at Tab 2.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II"><UNDER>PART II&mdash;ISSUES</UNDER></TI>
<P><BOLD>ISSUE 1:</BOLD> What is the standard of review for this appeal?</P>
<P><BOLD>ISSUE 2:</BOLD> Did the Honourable Justice Wilson err in law in her interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> to find that the Court could exercise its inherent jurisdiction to order separate hearings on the issues of liability and damages, even where the Appellants (Plaintiffs) do not consent to bifurcate the trial?</P>
<P><BOLD>ISSUE 3:</BOLD> Did the Honourable Justice Wilson err in her interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> to find that the Rule was limited to the Court's jurisdiction to bifurcate jury trials only, despite the fact that the plain reading of the Rule informs that it applies to all trials?</P>
<P><BOLD>ISSUE 4:</BOLD> Did the Honourable Justice Wilson err in law in finding that Master Donald E. Short was not bound by the finding of this Honourable Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael, et al v. Potrebic et al.</SOC></CASEREF>, and the Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>?</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III"><UNDER>PART III&mdash;THE LAW</UNDER></TI>
<P>7. Prior to the enactment of 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> the Court derived it's inherent jurisdiction from common law to control the process of the Court, which included the conduct of a trial.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC><CITE>2010 ONCA 126</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2010] O.J. No. 643</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, leave to appeal to SCC refused, 2010 CanLII 37855 (SCC), at paras. 15-16. Appellants' Book of Authorities (&ldquo;BOA&rdquo;), Tab 1.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Elcano Acceptance Ltd. et al. v. Richmond, Richmond, Stambler &amp; Mills</SOC><CITE>1986 CanLII 2591</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>. BOA, Tab 2.</P1></P>
<P>8. Case law prior to the enactment of Rule 6.1.01 cautioned that the Court's jurisdiction to bifurcate trials be narrowly circumscribed and exercised in only the clearest of cases, where it was in the interest of justice to do so. Jurisprudence noted that the Court should be slow to exercise the power in the face of an objection by one of the parties.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v Potrebic</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3655 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>13-14</PARANUM></CASEREF>. BOA, Tab 3.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Elcano Acceptance Ltd. et al. v. Richmond, Richmond, Stambler &amp; Mills</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>. BOA, Tab 2.</P1></P>
<P>9. in November 2007, former Associate Chief Justice Coulter Osbourne made recommendations to the Rules Committee regarding changes to be made to the civil justice system. Regarding bifurication, the following recommendation was made:
<QUOTE><P>The Civil Rules Committee should consider addressing bifurcation in a rule that would permit an order for bifurcation to be made on motion by any party or on the court's own initiative, after hearing from the parties. Any rule permitting bifurcation could reference some or all of the 14 factors listed in <CASEREF><SOC>Bourne v. Saunby</SOC></CASEREF>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <BOLD>Civil Justice Reform Project, List of Recommendations</BOLD>, October 29, 2015, BOA, Tab 4.</P1></P>
<P>9. <CASEREF><SOC>Bourne v. Saunby</SOC></CASEREF> was a case where the plaintiff's motor vehicle and a train collided. There were numerous defendants and third parties - including the Canadian National Railway Company and two municipalities. In Justice Tobias' 1993 decision, bifurcation was denied. The following factors were considered:
<P1>i. are the issues to be tried simple;</P1>
<P1>ii. are the issues of liability clearly separate from the issues of damages;</P1>
<P1>iii. is the factual structure upon which the action is based so extraordinary and exceptional that there is good reason to depart from normal practice requiring that liability and damages be tried together;</P1>
<P1>iv. does the issue of causation touch equally upon the issues of liability and damages;</P1>
<P1>v. will the trial judge be better able to deal with the issues of the injuries of the plaintiff and his financial losses by reason of having first assessed the credibility of the plaintiff during the trial of the issue of damages;</P1>
<P1>vi. can a better appreciation of the nature and extent of injuries and consequential damage to the plaintiff be more easily reached by trying the issues together;</P1>
<P1>vii. are the issues of liability and damages so inextricably bound together that they ought not to be severed;</P1>
<P1>viii. if the issues of liability and damages are severed, are facilities in place which will permit these two separate issues to be tried expeditiously before one court or before two separate courts, as the case may be;</P1>
<P1>ix. is there a clear advantage to all parties to have liability tried first;</P1>
<P1>x. will there be a substantial saving of costs;</P1>
<P1>xi. is it certain that the splitting of the case will save time, or will it lead to unnecessary delay;</P1>
<P1>xii. has there been an agreement by the parties to the action on the quantum of damages;</P1>
<P1>xiii. if a split be ordered, will the result of the trial on liability cause other plaintiffs in companion actions, based on the same facts, to withdraw or settle; and,</P1>
<P1>xiv. is it likely that the trials on liability will put an end to the action.
<P2><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Bourne v. Saunby</SOC><CITE>[1993] O.J. No. 2606</CITE><PARANUM>30</PARANUM></CASEREF>. BOA, Tab 5.</P2></P1></P>
<P>10. Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> was enacted in 2008. The new Rule came into force on January 1, 2010.</P>
<P>11. Justice Osbourne's recommendations were not followed by the Rules Committee, where the new Rule 6.1.01 is as follows:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>6.1.01</N><TI>SEPARATE HEARINGS</TI>
<SECP>With the consent of the parties, the court may order a separate hearing on one or more issues in a proceeding, including separate hearings on the issues of liability and damages.</SECP></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1>Ref: <BOLD><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></BOLD>, O. Reg. 438/08, Rule 6.1.01, Factum of the Appellant, Tab B-1.</P1></P>
<P>12. Prior to January 1, 2010, the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> allowed bifurcation pursuant to Rule 5.05, where the joinder of multiple claims or parties in the same proceeding may unduly complicate or delay the hearing or cause undue prejudice to a party. Rule 5.05 <UNDER>does not require consent from the parties</UNDER>.</P>
<P>13. The former Rule 73 of the <EM>Judicature Act of Ontario and Rules of Practice</EM> (1983),<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Judicature Act of Ontario and Rules of Practice (1983), vol. 1, at p. 887ff</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> provided that where several causes of action are joined in one action the court &ldquo;may direct the issues respecting the separate causes of action to be tried separately.&rdquo;
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <BOLD><EM>Judicature Act of Ontario and Rules of Practice (1983)</EM></BOLD>, vol. 1, at p. 887ff, as referenced in <CASEREF><SOC>Elcano Acceptance Ltd. et al. v. Richmond, Richmond, Stambler &amp; Mills</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>. BOA, Tab 2.</P1></P>
<P>14. In <CASEREF><SOC>Elcano Acceptance Ltd. et al. v. Richmond, Richmond, Stambler &amp; Mills</SOC></CASEREF>, the Ontario Court of Appeal considered the former Rule 73 and noted the language had not been carried forward to the new Rule 5.05.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Elcano Acceptance Ltd. et al. v. Richmond, Richmond, Stambler &amp; Mills</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>. BOA, Tab 2.</P1></P>
<P>15. Section 148 of the former <EM>Courts of Justice Act, 1984 (Ont.)</EM>, c. 11., and Section 138 of the current <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM> are identical: &ldquo;As far as possible, multiplicity of legal proceedings shall be avoided.&rdquo;
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <BOLD><EM>Courts of Justice Act, 1984 (Ont.)</EM></BOLD>, c. 11., s. 148, Factum of the Appellant, Tab B-2.</P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM></BOLD>, RSO 1990, c C.43, s. 138, Factum of the Appellant, Tab B-3.</P1></P>
<P>16. In <CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada Inc. v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, the Ontario Court of Appeal found that Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> does not apply to summary judgment motions.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada Inc. v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC><CITE>2018 ONCA 239 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>34 to 39</PARANUM></CASEREF>. BOA Tab 6.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV"><UNDER>PART IV&mdash;ARGUMENT</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N><UNDER><EM>1:</EM></UNDER></N><TI><UNDER><EM>Correctness Standard of Review</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>17. The correct standard of review for this appeal is correctness.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>[2002] 2 SCR 235</CITE><PARANUM>8-9</PARANUM></CASEREF>. BOA Tab 7. <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 12. BOA Tab 3.</P1></P>
<P>18. A decision of a master will be interfered with only if the master made an error of law or exercised his or her discretion on wrong principles or misapprehended the evidence such that there was a palpable or overriding error.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Zeitoun v. The Economical Insurance Group</SOC><CITE>2009 ONCA 415 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>1</PARANUM></CASEREF>. BOA Tab 8.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N><UNDER><EM>2:</EM></UNDER></N><TI><UNDER><EM>Correct Interpretation of Rule 6.1.01</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>19. The Defendant seeks to have separate hearings for liability and damages. The Plaintiffs do not consent.</P>
<P>20. This is not a case where Rule 5.05 applies - there is only one Defendant, one proceeding, and one cause of action. When considering bifurcation, the Court <UNDER>must</UNDER> consider Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</P>
<P>21. Bifurcation is the extreme exception to the rule against multiplicity of proceedings.</P>
<P>22. The following is an exhaustive list of cases where motions were brought, pursuant to Rule 6.1.01, and bifurcation was denied:
<P1>i. <CASEREF><SOC>Trinity Anglican Church v. Janeiro</SOC><CITE>[2012] OJ. No. 3791</CITE></CASEREF>, BOA Tab 9.</P1>
<P1>ii. <CASEREF><SOC>Robichaud v. Constantinidis</SOC><CITE>[2018] OJ. No. 3606</CITE></CASEREF>, BOA Tab 10.</P1>
<P1>iii. <CASEREF><SOC>Florence v. Benzaquen</SOC><CITE>[2016] OJ. No. 160</CITE></CASEREF>, BOA Tab 11.</P1>
<P1>iv. <CASEREF><SOC>O'Brien v. Universal Workers Union</SOC><CITE>[2015] OJ. No. 5965</CITE></CASEREF>, BOA Tab 12.</P1>
<P1>v. <CASEREF><SOC>Chandra v. Canadian Broadcasting Corp.</SOC><CITE>[2015] O.J. No. 4043</CITE></CASEREF>, BOA Tab 13.</P1>
<P1>vi. <CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton (City) v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>[2015] OJ. No. 852</CITE></CASEREF>, BOA Tab 14.</P1>
<P1>vii. <CASEREF><SOC>Soulliere (Litigation guardian of) v. Robitaille Estate</SOC><CITE>[2013] OJ. No. 3631</CITE></CASEREF>, BOA Tab 15.</P1>
<P1>viii. <CASEREF><SOC>Wm. Whiteley Ltd. v. Gauthier</SOC><CITE>[2010] OJ. No. 149</CITE></CASEREF>, BOA Tab 16.</P1></P>
<P>23. Where the parties consent to bifurcation of the trial, a motion is still required for the Court to consider whether the bifurcation order should be granted. The Court may chose not to bifurcate the trial, even if the parties consent. Such an Order would be similar to the Court refusing to grant an adjournment of a trial or refusing to transfer the location of a trial, even where the parties consent to the remedy sought. The wording of Rule 6.1.01 maintains the Court's inherent jurisdiction to deny bifurcation if it is not in the inter est of justice to do so.</P>
<P>24. In this way, the wording of Rule 6.1.01 clearly stipulates that the consent of the parties is a condition precedent to the Court considering whether or not bifurcation should be ordered. Crucially, there is no distinction drawn between jury and non-jury proceedings in the language of the Rule, which is plain and unambiguous on its face.</P>
<P>25. Only after the parties consent to bifurcation does the Court apply the factors set out in <CASEREF><SOC>Bourne v. Saunby</SOC></CASEREF>. It does not have inherent jurisdiction to make the determination where the condition precedent of consent is not present.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Bourne v. Saunby</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 30. BOA, Tab 5.</P1></P>
<P>26. The Rules Committee expressly narrowed the Court's jurisdiction to order bifurcation of trials in enacting Rule 6.1.01. The Court can exercise its inherent jurisdiction in a manner that does not conflict with the Rules or Statute. Further, a court's authority to invoke its inherent jurisdiction is to be used sparingly, and only in a clear case in which justice and fairness compel such recourse.
<P1>Ref: <CASEREF><SOC>Ziebenhaus v. Bahlieda</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 138 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>48 to 73</PARANUM></CASEREF>. BOA Tab 17.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Rose</SOC><CITE>1998 CanLII 768</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para. 33. BOA Tab 18.</P1></P>
<P>27. In writing for the majority of this Honourable Court, Justice Molloy correctly articulated Rule 6.1.01 in the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>. At paragraph 13, Mollloy J., explained:
<QUOTE><P>On a plain reading of Rule 6.1.01, a motion judge has a discretion to order bifurcation, but only if all parties consent. Even with the consent of the parties, the court is not required to order bifurcation, but without consent he or she has no power to do so. In other words, the consent of the parties is a pre-condition to the exercise of the discretion. [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Ref: <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 12. BOA Tab 3.</P1></P>
<P>28. The Ontario Court of Appeal has commented on Rule 6.1.01 twice. First in <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>, and again in <CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada Inc. v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>. BOA Tab 1.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada Inc. v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 34 to 39. BOA Tab 6.</P1></P>
<P>29. In <CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada Inc. v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC></CASEREF> the Ontario Court of Appeal relied on this Honourable Court's majority decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>. Chief Justice George R. Strathy adopted Justice Molloy's interpretation of Rule 6.1.01.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada Inc. v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 34 to 39. BOA Tab 6.</P1></P>
<P>31. In <CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton (City) v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF>, Justice Hambly found that Rule 6.1.01 is clear that bifurcation can only be ordered if the parties consent.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton (City) v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 19. BOA Tab 14.</P1></P>
<P>32. In <CASEREF><SOC>Wm. Whiteley Ltd. v. Gauthier</SOC></CASEREF>, Justice Turnbull found that, as a result of Rule 6.1.01, he lacked jurisdiction to grant bifurcation in the absence of the consent of the parties.
<P1>Ref: <CASEREF><SOC>Wm. Whiteley Ltd. v. Gauthier</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 5&ndash;9. BOA Tab 16.</P1></P>
<P>30. In drafting Rule 6.1.01, the Rules committee specifically required the consent of the parties prior to bifurcation. Explicit wording informs the Court that consent of all parties is required under Rule 6.1.01, especially in comparison to Rule 5.05, which provides the Court with broader jurisdiction to bifurcate where the joinder of multiple claims or parties in the same proceeding may unduly complicate or delay the hearing or cause undue prejudice to a party.</P>
<P>31. The ordinary meaning of a statutory provision is important. Use of different words implies a legislative intention to express different meanings. As noted in <CASEREF><SOC>Teal Cedar Products Ltd. v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF>, the modern principle of statutory interpretation requires that due importance be given to the ordinary meaning of a statute:
<QUOTE><P>The modern principle of statutory interpretation is well-established:
<QUOTE><P>Today there is only one principle or approach, namely, the words of an Act are to be read in their entire context and in their grammatical and ordinary sense harmoniously with the scheme of the Act, the object of the Act, and the intention of Parliament.</P>
<P>(E. A. Driedger, Construction of Statutes (2nd ed. 1983), at p. 87)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>This principle requires that statutes &ldquo;be read to give the words their most obvious ordinary meaning which accords with the context and purpose of the enactment in which they occur&rdquo;: <CASEREF><SOC>CanadianOxy Chemicals Ltd. v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>1999 CanLII 680</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1999] 1 S.C.R. 743</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Rizzo &amp; Rizzo Shoes Ltd. (Re)</SOC><CITE>1998 CanLII 837</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1998] 1 S.C.R. 27</CITE><PARANUM>21-22</PARANUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>. The plain and ordinary meaning of a statutory provision is the &ldquo;natural meaning which appears when the provision is simply read through&rdquo;....</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> Ruth Sullivan, <BOLD>Sullivan on the Construction of Statutes</BOLD>, 6th ed. (Markham: LexisNexis Canada, 2014), at p. 218, BOA Tab 19.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Teal Cedar Products Ltd. v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2017 SCC 32 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>111 and 112</PARANUM></CASEREF>. BOA Tab 20.</P1></P>
<P>33. Master Short and Justice Wilson both concluded that <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>, caused a fundamental shift in the parameters of how civil litigation is to be conducted. This interpretation of <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF> is too broad. The Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>, found that the summary judgment motion judge correctly applied his powers pursuant to Rule 20.04 (2.1) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. The Court concluded that Rule 20 was amended in 2010 to improve access to justice. The issue to be determined on a summary judgement is whether or not there is a genuine issue requiring a trial. The Supreme Court of Canada found that the summary judgment rules must be interpreted broadly, favouring proportionality and fair access to the affordable, timely and just adjudication of claims.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <BOLD>Decision of Master Short</BOLD>, at paras. 45-46, and 62. Appellants' Appeal Book and Compendium, at Tab 7.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Decision of Justice Wilson</BOLD>, at paras. 62&ndash;69, Appellants' Appeal Book and Compendium, at Tab 5.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF>. BOA Tab 21.</P1></P>
<P>34. The fundamental ratio of <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>, is that the summary judgement motion judge correctly applied his powers as afforded to him by the plain meaning of Rule 20.04 (2.1) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. The Court was not asked to consider bifurcation or Rule 6.1.01 in <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>. The Regulation changing the summary judgment Rule that was upheld and interpreted in <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>, is the same Regulation that enacted Rule 6.1.01 - O. Reg. 438/08. It is incorrect to conclude that one case interpreting one particular Rule that came into force in 2010 somehow changes and effects the meaning a completely different and unrelated Rule that also came into force at the same time.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>. BOA Tab 21.</P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></BOLD>, O. Reg. 438/08, Rule 20.04, Factum of the Appellant, Tab B-1.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N><UNDER><EM>3:</EM></UNDER></N><TI><UNDER><EM>Rule 6.1.01 Applies to All Trials - Jury &amp; Non-Jury</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>32. A plain reading of Rule 6.1.01 dictates that it applies to all trials. The wording of the Rule does not differentiate between jury trials and non-jury trials. This is entirely consistent with the goal of streamlining the judicial process and avoiding unnecessary steps in the litigation. Bifurcation of a trial can result in a multiplicity of proceedings which the Rules Committee was attempting to limit.</P>
<P>33. Neither the Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada, v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>., nor this Honourable Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>, interpret Rule 6.1.01 as applying only to jury trials but not to non-jury trials, or vice versa.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada Inc. v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 34 to 39. BOA Tab 6.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 12. BOA Tab 3.</P1></P>
<P>34. Chief Justice George R. Strathy adopted this interpretation of the Rule where he deliberately underlined the word &ldquo;trial&rdquo; at paragraph 34 of the Ontario Court of Appeal's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada Inc. v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>The majority of the Divisional Court held, at paras. 37-38, that a judge did not have inherent jurisdiction to bifurcate a <UNDER>trial</UNDER> into a determination of liability and a damage assessment without the consent of the parties. [Emphasis in Original]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada Inc. v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 34 to 39. BOA Tab 6.</P1></P>
<P>35. At paragraphs 25 and 26, this Honourable Court's majority decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF> stated:
<QUOTE><P>...the clear intent of the Rule was to require consent before any trial could be bifurcated, whether jury or judge alone. The Rule itself makes no distinction between a jury trial and a non-jury trial. If the effect of the new Rule is that there can be bifurcation of a jury trial, but only on consent of all parties, that effect must apply equally to all trials, whether jury or non-jury.</P>
<P>In my view, such an interpretation is also consistent with a plain and ordinary reading of the Rule. The Rules Committee clearly intended to impose a Rule as to when a judge has the power to exercise a discretion with respect to bifurcation of a trial. That discretion, according to the Rule, only arises where the parties consent.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 25-26. BOA Tab 3.</P1></P>
<P>35. The Ontario Court of Appeal decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>, is commonly misinterpreted to mean that the consent of the parties required pursuant to Rule 6.1.01 is limited only to jury trials.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>. BOA Tab 1.</P1></P>
<P>36. In <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal ultimately found that Rule 6.1.01 did not apply to that particular case because the Rule came into force after the original motion before Master Egan, on November 26, 2007.
<P1>Ref: <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>. BOA Tab 1.</P1></P>
<P>37. In writing for the panel, Justice Blair provided clarity on the newly enacted Rule 6.1.01. Justice Blair's direction on the Rule does not differentiate between jury and non jury trials. In fact, Justice Blair specifically stated that Rule 6.1.01 includes a judge's ability to bifurcate jury trials, on consent of the parties, despite the fact that pervious case law stood for the proposition that jury trials could never by bifurcated:
<QUOTE><P>Rule 6.1.01&mdash;effective January 1, 2010&mdash;is the first time a rule speaking to bifurcation has been promulgated. It signals that, in the opinion of the Rules Committee at least, the bifurcation of a trial, jury or non-jury, is not generally a good idea unless the parties consent. To repeat, rule 6.1.01 states:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>6.1.01</N><SECP>With the consent of the parties, the court may order a separate hearing on one or more issues in a proceeding, including separate hearings on the issues of liability and damages.</SECP></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>This new rule may well permit the bifurcation of issues of fact or of mixed fact and law even where a jury notice has been filed, where the parties consent, thus surmounting the jurisdictional impediments previously in place.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>The safer approach&mdash;for which the Rules Committee has now opted&mdash;is not to permit bifurcation in jury cases unless there is consent. Where there is consent, one party freely gives up its right to have the issues tried by a single jury.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 33,34 and 38. BOA Tab 1.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>38. Rule 1.04 states that the Rules of Civil Procedure &ldquo;shall be liberally construed.&rdquo; It is not in keeping with Rule 1.04 to narrowly interpret Rule 6.1.01 to mean that it only applies to jury trials.</TI></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N><UNDER><EM>4:</EM></UNDER></N><TI><UNDER><EM>Stare Decisis</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>39. Master Short and the Honourable Justice Wilson were bound by the majority decision of Justice Molloy of this Honourable Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF> and the Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>40. <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF> was a unanimous decision. Leave to Appeal to the Supreme Court of Canada was refused.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>. BOA Tab 1.</P1></P>
<P>41. Justice Blair's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF> must be found to be persuasive, if not binding, on all lower courts. Justice Blair's interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 occurred in the framework of the Court's simultaneous consideration and analysis of all bifurcation case law dating back to 1979.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>. BOA Tab 1.</P1></P>
<P>42. Justice Molloy's majority decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF> is similarly binding on all lower courts. Justice Molloy's interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 is correct. This is particularly evidenced by the fact that Chief Justice Strathy quoted the majority's interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 written by Justice Molloy, verbatim, in the Court of Appeal's decision of in <CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada Inc. v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Mars Canada Inc. v. Bemco Cash &amp; Carry Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 34 to 39. BOA Tab 6.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 12. BOA Tab 3.</P1></P>
<P>43. Since the decision of Master Donald E. Short in this case, Justice Akbarali released her decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Robichaud et al v. Constantinidis et al.</SOC></CASEREF>, where she found that the Court was bound by the decisions of <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>, notwithstanding <CASEREF><SOC>Carter v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF>.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Robichaud v. Constantinidis</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, BOA Tab 10.</P1></P>
<P>44. Justice Wilson incorrectly applied <CASEREF><SOC>Carter v. Canada (AG)</SOC></CASEREF>, in making her conclusion that she and Master Short did not need to follow the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>. Justice Wilson was also notably silent on whether she and Master short were bound by the Ontario Court of Appeal decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <BOLD>Decision of Justice Wilson</BOLD>, at paras. 60&ndash;64, and 68. Appellants' Appeal Book and Compendium, at Tab 5.</P1></P>
<P>45. <CASEREF><SOC>Carter v. Canada (AG)</SOC></CASEREF> is a 2015 Supreme Court of Canada decision in which the Court found that lower Courts were not necessarily bound by <EM>stare decisis</EM> where there has been a change in the law. The Court acknowledged that there had been a fundamental societal shift surrounding the issues of assisted suicide since it's 1993 decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Rodriguez v. British Columbia (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF>. The Court found that lower Courts are not bound by <EM>stare decisis</EM> if there is a new legal issue at bar, and if circumstances or evidence have &ldquo;fundamentally shift[ed] the parameters of the debate.&rdquo;
<P1>Ref: <CASEREF><SOC>Carter v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2015 SCC 5 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>44</PARANUM></CASEREF>. BOA Tab 22.</P1></P>
<P>46. In this case, Rule 6.1.01 is not a recent and fundamental change in the law. This Honourabl e Court, as well as the Court of Appeal, have interpreted Rule 6.1.01 in the decisions of <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>. There has been no change in the law regarding bifurcation since <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF> were released. This is not an appropriate case for a lower court to circumvent <EM>stare decisis</EM> pursuant to <CASEREF><SOC>Carter v. Canada (AG)</SOC></CASEREF>.
<P1><UNDER>Ref:</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>. BOA Tab 1.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 12. BOA Tab 3.</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V"><UNDER>PART V&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</UNDER></TI>
<P>47. The Appellant therefore respectfully submits that the Honourable Justice Wilson erred in finding that the Court could exercise its inherent jurisdiction to Order bifurcation of the trial in relation to the issues of liability and damages, where Rule 6.1.01 requires the consent of both parties as a condition precedent.</P>
<P>48. The Appellant submits that these are appropriate circumstances to reverse Master Short's Order bifurcating the liability and damages of this action on the basis that Master Short made an error in his interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, and he did not have jurisdiction to make this Order where the Appellants do not consent to the bifurcation.</P>
<P>49. The Plaintiffs also request costs of this motion on a partial indemnity basis fixed and payable by the Defendant.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED THIS 16th day of November, 2018</P>
<P>&ellip35; <BOLD>Thomas J. Hanrahan</BOLD></P>
<P>Lawyer for the Plaintiffs</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
