<BLOCK0><TI>FACTUM OF THE DEFENDANT/RESPONDENT</TI>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW STATEMENT</TI>
<P>1. The Appellants/Plaintiffs appeal the decision of Justice Wilson dated April 4, 2018 upholding the August 25, 2017 decision of Master Short wherein he granted, <EM>inter alia</EM>, the Respondent's motion to bifurcate the trial on the issues of liability and damages.</P>
<P>2. The Appellants have been granted leave to appeal Justice Wilson's order on the issue of jurisdiction only.</P>
<P>3. The Respondent opposes the appeal as it takes the position that Master Short had jurisdiction to grant the bifurcation order.</P>
<P>4. The within action arises from injuries sustained by the then four-year old Plaintiff/Appellant [G.D.] when he fell 10&ndash;15 feet after climbing over a balcony railing of a unit leased to his mother by the Defendant/Respondent Durham Region Non-Profit Housing Corporation on September 12, 2010.</P>
<P>5. On May 8, 2017, the Appellants brought a motion seeking to extend the time to set the within action down for trial to from March 21, 2017 to March 21, 2020. The Respondent opposed that motion and brought a cross-motion seeking bifurcation of the trial on the issues of liability and damages.</P>
<P>6. Both motions were heard by Master Short who granted:
<P1>a) The Respondent's motion to bifurcate the trial on the issues of liability and damages; and</P1>
<P1>b) The Appellants' motion for an extension of the deadline to set the action down for trial to March 31, 2020.</P1></P>
<P>7. On April 4, 2018, Justice Wilson dismissed the Appellant's appeal from the Order of Master Short on the basis that bifurcation was in the interests of justice. In doing so, she found that Master Short was correct and not bound by contrary precedent in finding that he had jurisdiction to make the bifurcation order.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>8. The Respondent accepts as correct the facts set out in paragraphs 3, 4 and 5 of the Appellants' Factum.</P>
<P>9. The Respondent disagrees with the facts as they are characterized in paragraphs 1, 2 and 6 of the Appellants' Factum.</P>
<P>10. The within action arises from injuries sustained by the then four-year old Plaintiff/Appellant [G.D.] on September 12, 2010, when he fell 10&ndash;15 feet after climbing over a balcony railing of a unit leased by the Defendant/Respondent to [G.]'s mother Jessica Knight.
<P1><BOLD>Statement of Claim issued March 21, 2012, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 11, p. 64, para. 11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>11. The Respondent accepts the contention that the extent and long-term effects of [G.]'s head injury are presently unknown.
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, para. 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>12. The key liability issues are the reasonableness of the Respondent's inspection and maintenance of the unit and the adequacy of the supervision provided by Ms. Knight in view of [G.]'s past history of climbing onto furniture and fixtures. Relevant expert reports and records have been exchanged and relevant witnesses have been identified.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 10, p. 54, para. 11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. The Respondent's employees with knowledge of the liability issues are elderly and have long been retired. Additionally, the former superintendent who carried out all of the unit inspections and repairs before and after [G.]'s fall was in poor health the last time he was seen by the Respondent's property manager.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 10, p. 57, paras. 20-21.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. On May 8, 2017, the Appellants brought a motion seeking to extend the time to set the within action down for trial from March 21, 2017 to March 21, 2020. The Respondent opposed that motion and brought a cross-motion seeking bifurcation of the trial on the issues of liability and damages.
<P1><BOLD>Notice of Motion dated February 22, 2017, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 8.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Decision of Master Short, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7, p. 27, paras. 7-8.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. Both motions were heard by Master Short who granted:
<P1>a) The Respondent's motion to bifurcate the trial on the issues of liability and damages; and</P1>
<P1>b) The Appellants' motion for an extension of the deadline to set the action down for trial to March 31, 2020.
<P2><BOLD>Reasons for Decision of Master Short dated August 25, 2017, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7, p. 40, para. 85.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>16. Master Short found that bifurcation was in the interests of justice and would furthermore have the significant advantage of potentially rendering unnecessary a lengthy and complex damages trial.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Decision of Master Short dated August 25, 2017, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7, p. 31, para. 36 and p. 36, para. 59.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. On April 4, 2018, Justice Wilson dismissed the Appellant's appeal from the Order of Master Short on the basis that bifurcation was in the interests of justice. In doing so, she found that Master Short was correct and not bound by contrary precedent in finding that he had jurisdiction to make the bifurcation order.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Decision of Justice Wilson dated February 26, 2018, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 3, p. 12, paras. 19&ndash;26 and p. 19, paras. 65-70.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. On October 11, 2018, the Appellants were granted leave to bring the within appeal of Justice Wilson's decision but only with respect to the issue of whether the Master had jurisdiction to bifurcate. Leave to appeal the issue of whether bifurcation ought to have been ordered, leaving aside the issue of jurisdiction, was specifically dismissed.
<P1><BOLD>Endorsement of the Divisional Court dated September 12, 2018, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 6.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ISSUES AND THE LAW</TI>
<P>19. The Position of the Respondent with respect to each issue raised by the Appellant is as follows:</P>
<P><BOLD>ISSUE 1:</BOLD> What is the standard of review for this appeal?</P>
<P>Respondent's Position: The Respondent agrees that the applicable standard of review is correctness.</P>
<P><BOLD>ISSUE 2:</BOLD> Did the Honourable Justice Wilson err in law in her interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 to find that the Court could exercise its inherent jurisdiction to order separate hearings on the issues of liability and damages, even where the Appellants (Plaintiffs) do not consent to bifurcate the trial?</P>
<P>Respondent's Position: No</P>
<P><BOLD>ISSUE 3:</BOLD> Did the Honourable Justice Wilson err in her interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 to find that the Rule was intended to limit the Court's jurisdiction to bifurcate jury trials only?</P>
<P>Respondent's Position: No</P>
<P><BOLD>ISSUE 4:</BOLD> Did the Honourable Justice Wilson err in law in finding that Master Short was not bound by the finding of this Honourable Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael, et al v. Potrebic et al.</SOC></CASEREF>, and the Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach v. Linn</SOC></CASEREF>?</P>
<P>Respondent's Position: No</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Issue"><N>1:</N><TI>The Standard of Review is Correctness</TI>
<P>20. The Respondent agrees that the standard of review for an appeal of a judge's order on pure questions of law is that of correctness. On questions of mixed fact and law and factual findings, the standard of review is palpable and overriding error, in which case considerable deference should be given and the lower court's decision should not be overturned unless there is evidence of &ldquo;overriding and palpable error&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 7 at paras. 8,10 and 36.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Issue"><N>2:</N><TI>The Correct Interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 is that the Rule does not oust the Court's Inherent Jurisdiction in relation to Bifurcation</TI>
<P>21. Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> provides that:
<QUOTE><P>With the consent of the parties, the court may order a separate hearing on one or more issues in a proceeding, including separate hearings on the issues of liability and damages.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> RRO 1990, Reg 194, R. 6.1.01, Appellants' Factum, Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Law Regarding Bifurcation prior to the Enactment of Rule 6.1.01</UNDER></TI>
<P>22. It was universally accepted prior to the enactment of Rule 6.1.01 that the court had inherent jurisdiction to bifurcate a proceeding in accordance with the 14 factors set out in <CASEREF><SOC>Bourne v. Saunby</SOC></CASEREF>. That jurisdiction was generally not exercised where one of the parties had served a jury notice. In non-jury cases, the court's inherent jurisdiction was exercised in exceptional cases.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Elcano Acceptance Ltd. v. Richmond, Richmond, Stambler and Mills</SOC><CITE>(1989) 55 OR (2d) 56</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 2.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bourne v. Saunby</SOC><CITE>[1993] OJ No 2606</CITE><COURTJUR>Gen. Div.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 5, p. 6-7, para. 30.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. The inherent jurisdiction of the court has been described as follows:
<QUOTE><P>As a superior court of general jurisdictions, the [Superior] Court of Ontario has all the powers that are necessary to do justice between the parties. Except where provided specifically to the contrary, the Court's jurisdiction is unlimited and unrestricted to substantive law in civil matters.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>80 Wellesley St. East Ltd. V. Fundy Bay Builders Ltd. Et al</SOC><CITE>[1972] 2 O.R. 280</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at p. 282, cited in in</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Ziebenhaus v. Bahlieda</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 138</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 17, p. 11, para. 48.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>24. The inherent jurisdiction of the court is a residual source of power derived from the very nature of the court as a superior court of law which the court may draw upon as necessary to prevent its process from being obstructed and abused and to secure a fair trial between the parties.
<P1><BOLD>Halbury's Laws of England, 4<SUP>th</SUP> ed. (London: Lexis-Nexis UK, 1973 - )vo. 37, at para. 14, cited in</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Stelco Inc. (re)</SOC><CITE>[2005] O.J. No. 1171</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para. 34, cited in</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Ziebenhaus v. Bahlieda</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 138</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 17, p. 15, para. 65.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. The Court may exercise its inherent jurisdiction in substantive matters, e.g., ordering a defence medical examination outside the authority for same provided in the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, as well as of procedural matters, .e.g., the manner in which an examination mandated by the Act is carried out.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ziebenhaus v. Bahlieda</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 138</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellant's Book of Authorities, Tab 17, p. 14-15, paras. 64-65.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>26. In <CASEREF><SOC>Woodbury (Litigation Guardian of) v. Woodbury</SOC></CASEREF>, Master Muir considered the factors set out <EM>Bourne</EM> in separating the issue of liability from the issue of damages. In concluding that the proceeding ought to bifurcated, Master Muir considered the complexity of the damages aspects as compared to the relatively simple issues on liability and the fact that there would be a significant saving in time and expense if the defendant was successful on liability. The combination of these factors indicated that a severance of issues for trial was an effective way to facilitate a more just, expeditious and less costly disposition of the trial process. Master Muir's decision was upheld on appeal by Justice Morgan who agreed with Master Muir's decision finding that the conclusion was consistent with the principle set out in Rule 1.04 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> in that bifurcation was the only way &ldquo;to secure the just, most expeditious and least expensive determination of every civil proceeding on its merits.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Woodbury (Litigation Guardian of) v. Woodbury</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 3149</CITE><COURTJUR>SCJ</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 1, paras 12 and 21.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Enactment of Rule 6.1.01</UNDER></TI>
<P>27. In 2006, former Attorney General, Michael Bryant, asked then Ontario Associate Chief Justice Coulter Osborne to lead the Civil Justice Reform Project (&ldquo;CJRP&rdquo;) to propose options that would reform the civil justice system to make it more accessible and affordable for Ontarians. In developing its recommendations, the CJRP was instructed to take into account four guiding principles:
<P1>1. Access: Recommendations should promote access to justice for both represented and unrepresented litigants;</P1>
<P1>2. Proportionality: Recommendations should reflect the principle that the time and expense devoted to civil proceedings should be proportionate to the amount in dispute and the importance of the issues at stake;</P1>
<P1>3. One size does not fit all: Recommendations should recognize diversity and the different issues facing different jurisdictions, particularly larger urban centres such as Toronto; and</P1>
<P1>4. Culture of litigation: Recommendations should recognize that rule and other regulatory reform alone might not adequately respond to problems in the system. Ways to foster &ldquo;cultural change&rdquo; among the bench and bar should be considered.
<P2><BOLD>Ontario, Ontario Ministry of Attorney General, Civil Justice Reform Project: Consultation Paper (Toronto: Ministry of Attorney General, 2006) at Appendix B, [Osborne Report], Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 2, p.2.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>28. Rule 6.1.01 was a recommendation of the CJRP. In Justice Osborne's report of recommendations to the Civil Rules Committee, he touched upon the issue of having a rule that would address power to order bifurcated proceedings. On this topic, Justice Osborne stated:
<QUOTE><P>The power to order issues in an action to be split into two or more trials is not expressly conferred by statute or the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. The power to order bifurcated proceedings appears to exist as part of the inherent jurisdiction of the court. In the leading case, the Court of Appeal held that it is a &ldquo;basic right&rdquo; of a litigant to have all issues in dispute resolved in one trial and that bifurcation must therefore be regarded as &ldquo;a narrowly circumscribed power.&rdquo;<SUP>96</SUP> In a later case, <CASEREF><SOC>Bourne v. Saunby</SOC></CASEREF>, the Ontario Court (General Division) listed fourteen criteria that the court should consider when evaluating the merits of a motion to sever liability from damages. The catalogue of factors set out in <EM>Bourne</EM>, though not an exhaustive list, is generally taken into account in determining whether bifurcation should be allowed. A decision of the Divisional Court suggests that a party's inability to fund the litigation is an &ldquo;extraneous&rdquo; factor that should not be considered when deciding whether to bifurcate a trial.<SUP>98</SUP></P>
<P>While I view bifurcation to be the exception, cost considerations militate in favour of bifurcation in some cases. In commercial litigation, for example, when dealing with damages will expose a party and sometimes all parties to significant costs, it may make sense to separate the issues of liability and damages and deal with liability first. Upon the determination of one issue, parties may be inclined to settle the balance of the issues in dispute. This can result in a significant savings of time, money and judicial resources. It would also be of particular benefit to those litigants who cannot afford a trial of all issues.</P>
<P>The Civil Rules Committee should consider addressing bifurcation in a rule that would permit an order for bifurcation to be made on motion by any party or on the court's own initiative, after hearing from the parties. Any rule permitting bifurcation could reference some or all of the 14 factors listed in <CASEREF><SOC>Bourne v. Saunby</SOC></CASEREF>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Osborne Report, ibid</EM> at Pre-Trials and Trial Management.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. Justice's Osbourne's commentary suggests that the recommendation to allow bifurcated civil proceedings is predicated on principles of proportionality, flexibility and affordability of the civil justice system. Allowing bifurcated proceedings recognizes that there are cases where the issues of liability and damages are so disproportionate in terms of time, cost, complexity that separating the issues would, in fact, result in the most just, cost-effective and expeditious use of time and resources.</P>
<P>30. The Appellants contend that Rule 6.1.01 ousted the inherent jurisdiction the court previously exercised in relation to bifurcation.
<P1><BOLD>Appellant's Factum, paras. 19&ndash;34</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. The law on this issue is that the ousting of the court's inherent jurisdiction has to be &ldquo;clear and precise&rdquo;. As stated by the court in <CASEREF><SOC>Ziebenhaus v. Bahlieda</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>Characterizing the issue by reference to whether legislation has &ldquo;occupied the field&rdquo; is either conclusory or misleading. The more appropriate, and precise, characterization of the scope of the court's inherent jurisdiction was addressed in <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Rose</SOC><CITE>1998 CanLII 768</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1998] 3 S.C.R. 262</CITE><PARANUM>33</PARANUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> where it is stated that, if the court's inherent jurisdiction is to be removed, that can only be accomplished by &ldquo;clear and precise language&rdquo;. This statement is also reflected in the decision of L'Heureux-Dube in Rose at para. 64 who, in affirming that Parliament can exclude the court's inherent jurisdiction by &ldquo;clear and precise statutory language indicating the contrary&rdquo;, cited and affirmed the following passage in I.H. Jacob, &ldquo;The Inherent Jurisdiction of the Court&rdquo; (1970) 23 Curr. Legal Pubs. 23 (the &ldquo;Jacob Article&rdquo;), at p. 24:</P>
<P>As a common law concept, the inherent jurisdiction is subject to the principle of parliamentary sovereignty. In I. H. Jacob, &ldquo;The Inherent Jurisdiction of the Court&rdquo; (1970), 23 Cum Legal Probs. 23, the author states at p. 24:</P>
<P>Moreover, the term &ldquo;inherent jurisdiction of the court&rdquo; is not used in contradistinction to the jurisdiction conferred on the court by statute. The contrast is not between the common law jurisdiction of the court on the one hand and its statutory jurisdiction on the other, for the court may exercise its inherent jurisdiction even in respect of matters which are regulated by statute or by rule of court, so long as it can do so without contravening any statutory provision.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ziebenhaus v. Bahlieda</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 138</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 17, p. 13, para. 57.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>32. The Divisional Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF> was divided in its interpretation of Rule 6.1.01.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3655</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>33. Justice Corbett's dissenting opinion <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> accords with Justice's Osbourne's vision of Rule 6.1.01. In speaking on the origins of the Rule, Justice Corbett made the following comments:
<QUOTE><P>While it would have been possible, of course, for the Rules Committee to reject the Osborne Report's recommendations outright and decide that the court's inherent jurisdiction to order separate trials was too broad as it was, this would have been a rather strange thing to do. There is no contemporary jurisprudence raising concern about overuse of, or difficulties caused by, improper use of the inherent jurisdiction to order separate trials. There is no academic commentary calling for scaling back of this power. There is no &ldquo;mischief&rdquo; at which Rule 6.1 was aimed if it is read as Molloy J. does. <BOLD>In this context, in my view, the common sense conclusion is that the Rules Committee decided to implement a portion of Justice Osborne's recommendations on this issue and not that the Rules Committee rejected the recommendations outright and narrowed the court's jurisdiction to order bifurcation.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Bondy-Rafael, ibid</EM> at p. 18-19, para. 74.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>34. Justice Corbett found that the plain meaning of Rule 6.1 did not entirely oust the court's inherent jurisdiction to control its own process. He further noted that the language of Rule 6.1 is permissive rather than exclusive.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Bondy-Rafael, ibid at</EM> p. 12&ndash;23, paras. 42&ndash;85.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>35. Rule 6.1 was intended to enhance the court's ability to fashion flexible and proportionate procedures, not to curtail the reasonable exercise of the court's inherent jurisdiction to promote justice.
<P1><EM>Bondy-Rafael, ibid at</EM> <BOLD>p.14, para 51.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>36. Justice Corbett in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC></CASEREF> disagreed with the majority's interpretation of the Court of Appeal decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach (Litigation Guardian of) v. Kovach</SOC></CASEREF>, noting that there is nothing in Kovach which concludes that Rule 6.1.01 completely ousts the court's jurisdiction.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Bondy-Rafael, ibid</EM> at p. 14, para. 54.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>37. In <CASEREF><SOC>Elcano Acceptance Ltd. v. Richmond</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal clearly stated that the court has inherent jurisdiction to order bifurcated trials where the interest of justice requires it.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Elcano Acceptance Ltd. v. Richmond, Richmond, Stanzbler and Mills</SOC><CITE>(1986) 55 OR (2d) 56</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 2, p. 4-5, para. 11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>38. Subsequent decisions in <CASEREF><SOC>O'Brien v Universal Workers Union</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Glasjam v. Freedman</SOC></CASEREF>, decided in respect of matters arising after the enactment of Rule 6.1.01, stand for the proposition that the Rules Committee did not remove the court's inherent jurisdiction to order separate hearings on liability and damages, albeit in the clearest of cases.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>O'Brien v Universal Workers Union (Labourers' International Union of North America, Local 183)</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 7005</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 12, p. 6-7, para. 28.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Glasjam v. Freedman</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 3878</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 3, p. 16, para. 77.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>39. Justice Corbett's dissent in <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> was cited with approval by Justice MacLeod in <CASEREF><SOC>Campbell v. Campbell</SOC></CASEREF>. MacLeod J. also agreed that Rule 6.1 did not stand for a universal proposition that the court does not have inherent jurisdiction to bifurcate the trial of an action. He noted the &ldquo;powerful dissent&rdquo; of Justice Corbett on the interpretation of Rule 6.1 and noted his preference for his analysis over that of the majority, noting that Corbett J's analysis was not only consistent with the trend of cases following the enactment of the Rule, but also the rationale for enacting the Rule.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Campbell v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 2139</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 4, p. 9, paras. 41-42.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>40. Further, in <CASEREF><SOC>Aprile Estate v. Aprile</SOC></CASEREF>, Justice Molly (who authored the majority reasons in <EM>Bondy-Rafael)</EM> provided the following comments:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>Rule 6.1.01 did not come into force until 2010. The issue of bifurcation under that rule has not been dealt with by the Divisional Court in the context of an oppression case. There was a vigorous dissent in Bondy-Raphael, which was a personal injury action.</BOLD> There are important issues involved with respect to the general principles of: the desirability of finding the most expeditious and least expensive ways of resolving disputes and whether bifurcation frustrates or facilitates that; the desirability of promoting early settlement and whether that can be fully informed without complete disclosure at an early stage; whether different principles for production should be applied in commercial litigation; and the burden on parties of complicated and expensive document production that might prove to be pointless if there is no finding of oppression. These principles have broad impact beyond the issues in this particular case. <BOLD>This is an area of the law that could benefit from appellate guidance, [emphasis added]</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Aprile Estate v. Aprile</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 7898</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 5 at para. 10.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>41. The Respondent submits that given the flux in this area of the law, it was open to Master Short to apply the factual matrix of this case to achieve the most just, cost-effective and expeditious use of time and judicial resources as contemplated by Rule 1.04 and by the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Hymiak</EM> (which Master Short refers to at paragraph 46 of his Reasons for Decision).
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>[2014] 1 SCR 87</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellant's Book of Authorities, Tab 21.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Appellants Do Not Have an Absolute Right to One Hearing</UNDER></TI>
<P>42. While a plaintiff has a presumptive right to have all issues dealt with in a single trial, the courts have made it clear that this right <BOLD>is not</BOLD> absolute and that bifurcation of issues in an action may be necessary to minimize delay and expense, better serve the interests of justice and result in greater litigation efficiency.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Florence v. Benzaquen</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 132</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 6 at para. 10.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>43. Courts have repeatedly granted bifurcation orders in &ldquo;exceptional cases&rdquo;. If the Appellants' arguments are to be accepted that such orders could only be granted where the parties consented, there would no need to analyze such requests through the exceptional case lens, as the court would be entirely prevented from granting such orders other than on consent.</P>
<P>44. The fact that jurisprudence has continued to develop in this area since the 2010 amendment clearly signals that the court continues to maintain inherent jurisdiction to make such orders where the interests of justice dictate.</P>
<P>45. Further, there is no explicit requirement in Rule 6.1.01 that bifurcation can only be granted &ldquo;with the consent of the parties&rdquo;. If that were the case, the legislature would have provided language clearly stating that <UNDER>&ldquo;only</UNDER> with the consent of the parties, the court may order a separate hearing...&rdquo;</P>
<P>46. Similarly, there is nothing in Rule 6.1.01 that provides that <EM>even where</EM> the parties consent to bifurcation, the court is <UNDER>required</UNDER> to so order; rather, the Rule provides that &ldquo;the court <EM>may</EM> order a separate hearing on one or more issues in the proceeding, including separate hearings on the issues of liability and damages&rdquo;.</P>
<P>47. Absent clear, unequivocal language, the Respondent submits that the court retains its inherent jurisdiction to undertake the necessary steps outlined in <EM>Bourne</EM>, which Master Short did, to determine whether or not bifurcation should be granted, irrespective of whether the parties consent or not.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Rules 1.04 and 20 can Assist in the Interpretation of Rule 6.1.01</UNDER></TI>
<P>48. Rule 1.04 provides that the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> &ldquo;shall be liberally construed to secure the just, most expeditious and least expensive determination of every civil proceeding on its merits&rdquo;.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> RRO 1990, Reg 194, r. 1.0, Appellants' Factum, Schedule B, Tab 1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>49. Rule 1.04 has been described as the &ldquo;single most important Rule of Civil Procedure&rdquo; and the rule that &ldquo;guides the interpretation of all the Rules&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Griffioen v. Liao</SOC><CITE>2003 CarswellOnt 5290</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 7 at para. 14.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Finlay v. Van Paassen</SOC><CITE>2010 ONCA 204</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 8 at para. 14.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>50. The Rule continues to be in the forefront for allowing courts to dispense with or vary application of the <EM>Rules</EM> provided that the dispensation or varied interpretation results in a just determination of the action on its merits. Courts have justified the application of Rule 1.04 on the basis that procedural rules are the servants of justice, not its masters and importance must be placed on their substance rather than their form.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Senechal v. Muskoka (District Municipality)</SOC><CITE>2005 CarswellOnt 1414</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 9 at para. 8.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>1248671 Ontario Inc. v. Michael Foods Inc.</SOC><CITE>2000 CarswellOnt 4263</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 10 at para. 19.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>51. The Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Hymiak</EM> emphasized that a shift away from conventional approaches was necessary to promote the timely and affordable resolution of disputes. In <EM>Hymiak</EM>, the Court stated:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>This shift entails simplifying pretrial procedures and moving the emphasis away from the conventional trial in favour of proportional procedures tailored to the needs of the particular case.</BOLD> The balance between procedure and access struck by our justice system must come to reflect modem reality and recognize that new models of adjudication can be fair and just.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>[2014] 1 SCR 87</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 21, p. 7 at para. 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>52. The intersectionality of Rule 1.04, Rule 6.1.01 and Rule 20 was addressed in <CASEREF><SOC>Fontenelle v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF> by Justice Price who commented on Master Short's discussion on the court's retention of jurisdiction to determine bifurcation in this case.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Fontenelle v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2017 O.J. No. 5678</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Book of Authorities of the Responding Party, Tab 11, p. 39&ndash;41, para 133&ndash;142.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>53. Master Short applied the spirit and legislative intent of Rule 6.1.01, guided by the principles of Rule 1.04 and <EM>Hryniak</EM>. Master Short noted that:
<QUOTE><P>My reading of the genesis of Rule 6.1 [is that it] was intended to enhance the court's ability to fashion flexible and proportionate procedures, not to curtail the reasonable exercise of the court's inherent jurisdiction to promote justice. I believe that this interpretation accords with the guidance of the Supreme Court in <EM>Hryniak</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Decision of Master Short, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7, p. 36, para. 62.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>54. The promotion of an expeditious and early resolution of a matter on its merits is in line with the spirit of Rule 1.04 and the Supreme Court of Canada's discussion in <EM>Hryniak</EM>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Morniga v. State Farm Mutual Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>[2002] O.J. No. 2094</CITE><PARANUM>18-19</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 12, p. 4, para 18-19.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Clifford v. MacKinnon</SOC><CITE>[2008] 93 O.R. (3d) 554</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 13, p. 3-4, paras. 9, 12.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Rule 36.01 is Not Appropriate in the Circumstances</UNDER></TI>
<P>55. At paragraph 33 of his decision, Master Short considered and correctly rejected the Appellant's suggestion that the Respondent take the evidence of its witnesses in advance of trial under Rule 36.01. Master Short reasoned that this approach was not satisfactory as &ldquo;viva voce evidence is always to be preferred&rdquo;.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Decision of Master Short dated August 25, 2018, Appeal Record and Compendium, Tab 7, p. 31, para. 33.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>56. This position is supported by Justice Murray in <CASEREF><SOC>Paiva v. Corpening</SOC></CASEREF>, who noted that it is a general principle in both civil and criminal cases that, if there is a trial, that evidence at trial should be presented orally in open court.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Paiva v. Corpening</SOC><CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 771</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 14, p. 5, para. 23.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>57. It goes without saying that viva voce evidence carries more weight than written records and a witness being in a box, subject to cross-examination and credibility determination is more persuasive to a trial judge that documentary evidence.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gauthier et al. v. Gauthier</SOC><CITE>2017 MBQB 116</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 15, para. 191.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>58. The only evidence offered by the Appellants in opposition to the Respondent's request for bifurcation was the inconvenience to the Plaintiffs of having to attend at trial twice, a reason which Master Short correctly rejected, at paragraph 36, as insufficient to trump the early consideration of the liability issues.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Decision of Master Short, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7, p. 6, para. 36.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Issue"><N>3:</N><TI>Application of Rule 6.1.01 to Non-Jury Trials</TI>
<P>59. The Appellants suggest that with the deliberate inclusion of the condition, &ldquo;with the consent of the parties&rdquo; in Rule 6.1.01, the Civil Rules Committee intended consent as a requirement and limitation on the Court's jurisdiction with respect to bifurcation of <UNDER>all</UNDER> trials&mdash;jury and non-jury.</P>
<P>60. Although the exact recommendation from Justice Osborne's report was not adopted by the Civil Justice Committee, a rule addressing bifurcation was ultimately included in the comprehensive 2010 amendments to the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, in which access to justice, affordability and proportionality were the overarching themes.
<P1><BOLD>Rule 6.1.01 of the Rules of Civil Procedure, O.Reg. 438/08.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>61. It was never the intention of the Civil Rules Committee to obfuscate the clear and ongoing common law right to bifurcation of a non-jury trial. As noted by Justice MacLeod in <EM>Campbell</EM>:
<QUOTE><P>In the first place, Bondy-Rafael was rendered by a split court with a powerful dissent concurring in the result and it dealt with Rule 6.1 of the Rules. It is a decision that is intentionally restrictive in its application and it does not apply to the case at bar. Insofar as the case stands for the proposition that Rule 6.1 of the Rules of Civil Procedure excludes any inherent jurisdiction to bifurcate an action, for purposes of this motion I do not have to decide whether that conclusion is binding upon me in similar circumstances. I would observe in passing that I prefer the analysis of Corbett J. to that of the majority. Justice Corbett's analysis of the rule is not only consistent with current judicial trends but with the rationale for enacting the rule. <BOLD>As it happens I was a participant in all of the deliberations of the Rules Committee considering the recommendations of the Osborne Report. I am certain that it was never the intent of the Rules Committee to &ldquo;occupy the field&rdquo; or to restrict the inherent jurisdiction of the court. [emphasis added]</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Campbell v Campbell</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 2139</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 4, p. 9, para. 42.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>62. Justice Wilson's interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 took into account the fact that Rule 6.1.1 was intended to improve accessibility and affordability to the justice system and ensure that the time and expense spent on a proceeding is proportionate to the amount in dispute or the importance of the issues at stake.</P>
<P>63. The Appellants' characterization of Rule 6.1.01 as completely eliminating the court's inherent discretion to order bifurcation in non-jury trials contradicts the purpose behind the CJRP that enacted the rule.</P>
<P>64. The Appellants contend that Justice Wilson erred in concluding that Rule 6.1.01 did not oust the court's inherent jurisdiction to order bifurcation unless the parties, as a pre condition, consent to separate hearings, and that consent is a precondition before bifurcation can be allowed; however, this argument ignores the principles of accessibility, affordability and proportionality which underlie the intent of the legislature in enacting the 2010 amendments including Rule 6.1.01.</P>
<P>65. Moreover, by imposing the Appellants' literal interpretation of Rule 6.1.01, not only is it inconsistent with the legislature's intention and object behind Rule 6.1.01 but it is also inconsistent with Rule 1.04 of the Rules of Civil Procedure.</P>
<P>66. At paragraph 68 of Justice Wilson's Reasons for Decision, she stated:
<QUOTE><P>Alternatively, if I am wrong in my conclusion that the Master was not bound by the <EM>obiter</EM> analysis in in <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM>, then I conclude relying on <EM>Carter</EM>, that the principles outlined in <EM>Hymiak</EM> trump the decision of the Divisional Court. The Master's order should be upheld. The parameters of the debate and guiding principles in the conduct of civil litigation dramatically shifted with <EM>Hymiak</EM> and should be applied.</P>
<P>Bifurcation in this case is efficient, and will promote settlement. Bifurcation of the liability and damages issues is in the interests of justice for the parties, consistent with the overarching purpose enunciated in Rule 1.04. This Rule provides that the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> are to &ldquo;be liberally construed to secure the just, most expeditious and least expensive determination of every civil proceeding on its merits.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Decision of Justice Wilson, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 3, p. 11, para. 68.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>67. We concur with Justice Wilson's conclusion that the intended purpose of Rule 6.1.010 was to modestly expand the jurisdiction of the court to allow bifurcation in jury trial in accordance with the new rules, but only with the consent of the parties.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Decision of Justice Wilson, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 3, p. 11, Tab 66.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Issue"><N>4:</N><TI>Stare Decisis</TI>
<P>68. It is well established law in Canada that lower courts are bound by the <EM>ratio decidendi</EM> of decisions from higher courts but they <BOLD><UNDER>are not</UNDER></BOLD> bound by all <EM>obiter dicta</EM> of decisions from higher courts. In <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Henry</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court of Canada explained that:
<QUOTE><P>all <EM>obiter dicta</EM> do not have, and are not intended to have, the same weight. The weight decreases as one moves from the dispositive <EM>ratio decidendi</EM> to a wider circle of analysis which is obviously intended for guidance and which should be accepted as authoritative. <BOLD>Beyond that, there will be commentary, examples or exposition that are intended to be helpful and may be found to be persuasive, but are certainly not &ldquo;binding&rdquo;</BOLD> in the sense that <EM>Sellars</EM> principle in its most exaggerated form would have it. The objective of the exercise is to promote certainty in the law, not to stifle its growth and creativity. <BOLD>The notion that each phrase in a judgment of this Court should be treated as if enacted in a statute is not supported by the cases and is inconsistent with the basic fundamental principle that the common law develops by experience.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Henry</SOC><CITE>[2005] 3 S.C.R. 609</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2005] S.C.J. No. 76</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>2005 SCC 76 (CanLII)</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 16, para. 57.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>69. In order to determine the portions of a decision that are binding the portions that non binding obiter, one must ask: what does the case actually decide?
<P1>Ibid.</P1></P>
<P>70. A legal pronouncement that is integral to the result or the analysis underlying the determination of the matter in any particular case will be binding. In some cases, the legal pronouncement may only be a narrow point in a specific factual context while in others, the court may set out legal analyses that have application beyond the facts of the particular case. Examples of the latter include the vast majority of Supreme Court of Canada decisions that set out the legal framework for novel issues.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R v. Prokofiew</SOC><CITE>2010 ONCA 423</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 17, at para. 20.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>71. On the other hand, obiter dicta that reach beyond the specific issue raised before a court or played no role in the reasoning of the court necessary to decide the specific issue before it is not binding.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R v. Hajivasilis</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 27</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 18, at para. 21.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>72. It is clear that Justice Wilson had considered and applied the legal principles cited above in arriving at her conclusion that the discussion in <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> respecting the application of Rule 6.1.01 to non-jury cases is non-binding obiter dictum and in this regard, she was not bound by it.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Decision of Justice Wilson, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 3, p. 15&ndash;17, paras. 47&ndash;53.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>73. In <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM>, the motion judge granted the defendants request to bifurcate the jury trial without the plaintiffs consent such that trial for determination of liability would proceed before the assessment of damages. On appeal, the Court stated that &ldquo;the central issue is whether the motion judge had any power to order bifurcation without the consent of all parties.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3655</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 3, p. 2, para. 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>74. The facts in <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> included:
<P1>a) Two minor Plaintiffs were involved in a motor vehicle accident wherein they sustained catastrophic injuries;</P1>
<P1>b) The minor Plaintiffs, their mother and brother commenced a claim against the driver of the vehicle that struck them as well as the municipality;</P1>
<P1>c) A jury notice was filed;</P1>
<P1>d) The trial was scheduled for eight weeks to commence in Windsor on September 8, 2014;</P1>
<P1>e) A few months prior to the trial date, the defendants learned of a material change in circumstances relevant to damages and, in particular, future care costs; and</P1>
<P1>f) The defendants also proposed using the September 8 trial date to deal only with the issue of liability and sought an order bifurcating the trial, so that the damages assessment would proceed subsequent to the determination of liability.
<P2><BOLD>Ibid.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>75. Ultimately, the motion judge as well as this Court in <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> held that a jury trial could not be bifurcated without the consent of all parties as dictated by Rule 6.1.01.
<P1><BOLD>Ibid.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>76. The discussion in <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> respecting the application of Rule 6.1.01 to non-jury cases was not integral to the result or the analysis underlying the determination of the issue before the court in that case, which was whether a motion judge can order the bifurcation of a jury trial without the consent of the parties.</P>
<P>77. Further, the underlying theme of the CJRP and which carried over into the post-Rule 6.1.1 cases, was the expansion of the court's ability to order bifurcation of jury trials upon consent of parties (whereas, previously the common law excluded such as an order even with consent). T he aim of the Rule was not, as the Appellants contend, to disrupt the common law inherent jurisdiction to bifurcate non-jury trials.</P>
<P>78. The Respondent concurs with Justice Wilson's conclusion at paragraph 65 of her decision that the ratio decidendi of <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> should be read as applying solely to jury trials.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Shift in Culture</UNDER></TI>
<P>84. Justice Wilson cited the Supreme Court of Canada's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Carter v Canada</SOC></CASEREF> for the principle that &ldquo;stare decisis is not a straightjacket that condemns the law to stasis. Trial courts may reconsider settled rulings of higher courts where a legal issue is raised or where there is a change in the circumstances or evidence that fundamentally shifts the parameters of the debate.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Decision of Justice Wilson, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 3, p. 18, paras. 60&ndash;62.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Carter v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2015 SCC 5</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 22, para 44.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>82. The facts and circumstances of this case differ fundamentally from <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> such that Justice Wilson correctly heeded the Supreme Court of Canada's direction in <EM>Carter</EM> that &ldquo;changes in circumstances or evidence that fundamentally shifts the parameters&rdquo; of whether a previous decision of a higher court ought to be restrictively adhered to.</P>
<P>85. It is submitted that Justice Wilson's characterization of the case law surrounding Rule 20 as bringing about a shift in culture towards more expeditious trial and pre-trial procedures, as detailed above, is widely accepted whereas the Appellants' characterization of the Rule 20 jurisprudence as simply case law interpreting a rule change is reflective of an unduly impoverished and narrow vision of the sea change advocated by <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 21.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>86. It is therefore submitted that this Honourable Court is not bound by its decision in <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM>.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART V&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>87. The Respondent respectfully requests that the within appeal of Justice Wilson's decision be denied with costs payable to the Respondent.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED THIS 16<SUP>th</SUP> day of January, 2019</P>
