<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">NOTICE OF MOTION FOR LEAVE TO APPEAL</TI>
<P>The Plaintiffs, moving party on appeal, will make a motion to the Divisional Court of Ontario, at Osgoode Hall, 130 Queen Street West, Toronto, Ontario for the motion to be heard on a date fixed by the Registrar.</P>
<P>PROPOSED METHOD OF HEARING: The motion is to be heard orally.</P>
<P>THIS MOTION IS FOR:
<P1>a) Leave to Appeal of the decision of the Honourable Justice J. Wilson, at Toronto, dated April 4, 2018;</P1>
<P1>b) The costs of this motion; and</P1>
<P1>c) Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P1></P>
<P>THE GROUNDS FOR THE MOTION ARE:
<P1>a) The learned Appeal Judge erred in applying Rules 20 and 50.07 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> and concluding that the Master had jurisdiction to bifurcate the issues of liability and damages;</P1>
<P1>b) The learned Appeal Judge misapplied the purpose of rule 6.1.01 of the Rules of Civil Procedure;</P1>
<P1>c) The learned Appeal Judge erred in applying section 138 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM> in failing to avoid a multiplicity of proceedings;</P1>
<P1>d) The learned Appeal Judge erred in law in determining that this was not an appropriate case in which to apply Rule 36.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>;</P1>
<P1>e) The learned Appeal Judge erred in law in determining that bifurcation was the only way to secure the just, most expeditious, and least expensive determination of every civil proceeding on its merits, as stated in Rule 1.04(1);</P1>
<P1>f) The learned Appeal Judge erred in law in finding that the Defendant met the high burden of proof to justify bifurcation;</P1>
<P1>g) The learned Appeal Judge failed to adequately take into consideration the best interests of the minor Plaintiff, a person under disability, when considering the implications of her Order;</P1>
<P1>h) The learned Appeal Judge created distinctions between jury and non jury matters where no such distinction exists in the Rules of Civil Procedure;</P1>
<P1>i) The learned Appeal Judge misapprehended the applicability of <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> and misapplied <EM>Hyrniak</EM>;</P1>
<P1>j) There is a clear conflict between cases: <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3655</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>128 O.R (3de) 767</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Campbell v Campbell</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 2139</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>27 E.T.R. (4th) 118</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Hyrniak v Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7 [2014]</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>1 S.C.R. 87</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> as well as <CASEREF><SOC>Elcano Acceptance Ltd. v Richmond</SOC><YEAR>1980</YEAR><CITE>55 OR (2d) 56</CITE></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Glasjam v Freedman</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 3878</CITE></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Woodbury (Litigation guardian of) v Woodbury</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 3149</CITE></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Bourne v Saunby</SOC><CITE>23 CPC (3d) 333</CITE></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Morniga v State Farm Mutual Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>[2002] OJ No 2094</CITE></CASEREF>;</P1>
<P1>k) There are serious issues to be determined on the proposed appeal;</P1>
<P1>e) Brief of Authorities of the moving party.</P1></P>
