<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>PART I: OVERVIEW</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. This Leave to Appeal/appeal concerns the right of a plaintiff in Ontario to have all issues in dispute decided in one trial.</P>
<P>2. This action arises out of a tragic accident on September 12, 2010 in which the Plaintiff, [G. D.] then only four years old, opened a defective sliding balcony door in a rental unit owned by the Defendant. [G.] climbed up over a balcony railing, and fell 10-15 feet to the ground below. As a result of this fall, [G.] suffered an undisplaced skull fracture and a closed head injury. This head injury has developed into a number of psychological, behavioural and developmental issues. Due to [G.]'s age the full extent of the brain injury sequelae is unclear.</P>
<P>3. The Plaintiffs brought a motion for an extension of time to set the within action down for trial from March 21, 2017 to March 21, 2020. The Defendant brought a cross-motion seeking an order bifurcating the trial on the issues of liability and damages. Both parties opposed each other's motions, returnable May 8, 2017.</P>
<P>4. Master Short granted each parties' order in his reasons released August 25, 2017.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II"><UNDER>PART II: ISSUES</UNDER></TI>
<P>5. The Plaintiffs submit that the standard of review is that of correctness.</P>
<P>6. The Plaintiffs submit that Justice Wilson made the following errors:
<P1>(a) In her interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> to find that she had jurisdiction to bifurcate the trial without the consent of all parties;</P1>
<P1>(b) In the alternative, if this Honourable Court accepts Master Short's interpretation of Rule 6.1.01, the Plaintiffs submit that Master Short made the following errors in his application of Rule 6.1.01:
<P2>(i) In finding that there was sufficient evidence to determine whether bifurcation was appropriate; and</P2>
<P2>(ii) In finding that the Defendants had satisfied the high threshold to justify bifurcation in these circumstances.</P2></P1>
<P1>(c) In her determination she was not bound by the finding of the Divisional court in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael, et al v Potrebic et al.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3655</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III"><UNDER>PART III: LAW AND FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><N><UNDER>A.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>The standard of review is correctness</UNDER></TI>
<P>7. There is no reasoned basis to distinguish between the decision of a master and that of a judge for the purposes of the standards of review on appeal. An appellate court cannot substitute its interpretation of the facts or reweigh the evidence simply because it takes a different view of the evidence from that of the master. On questions of law, the correctness standard applies.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Wellwood v Ontario Provincial Police</SOC><CITE>2010 ONCA 186</CITE><PARANUM>28</PARANUM></CASEREF>, citing <CASEREF><SOC>Zeitoun v The Economical Insurance Group</SOC><CITE>2009 ONCA 415</CITE><PARANUM>1</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities (&ldquo;BOA&rdquo;) Tab A.</P1></P>
<P>8. This appeal deals with the proper statutory interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. This is a question of law. The standard of review is correctness.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Housen v Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33</CITE><PARANUM>8-9</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab B.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><UNDER>B.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Errors in Justice Wilson's interpretation of Rule 6.1.01</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><N><UNDER>(i)</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>The interpretation of Rule 6.1.01</UNDER></TI>
<P>9. In <CASEREF><SOC>Elcano Acceptance Ltd. v Richmond, Richmond, Stambler and Mills</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal held that a judge's inherent jurisdiction to bifurcate a proceeding was a narrowly circumscribed power. This power is a departure from the basic right of litigants to have all issues in dispute decided in one trial and <EM>ought therefore to be exercised only in exceptional cases</EM>.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Elcano Acceptance Ltd. v Richmond, Richmond, Stambler and Mills</SOC><YEAR>1989</YEAR><CITE>55 OR (2d) 56</CITE><PARANUM>11</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab C.</P1></P>
<P>10. After <EM>Elcano</EM>, when the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> were amended in 2010, there were recommendations that bifurcation be available either on motion by the parties or on the Court's own initiative. That recommendation was <EM>not</EM> adopted.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach (Litigation Guardian of) v Kovach</SOC><CITE>2010 ONCA 126</CITE><PARANUM>33 &amp; 38</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab D.</P1></P>
<P>11. In 2010, the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> were amended. Rule 6.1.01 provides as follows:
<QUOTE><P><EM>With the consent of the parties</EM>, the court may order a separate hearing on one or more issues in a proceeding, including separate hearings on the issues of liability and damages.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990, Reg 194 rule 6.1.01 [emphasis added].</P1></P>
<P>12. Provisions in an act are to be interpreted &ldquo;in their entire context and in their grammatical and ordinary sense harmoniously with the scheme of the Act, the object of the Act, and the intention of Parliament&rdquo;.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Bell ExpressVu Limited Partnership v Rex</SOC><CITE>[2002] 2 SCR 559</CITE><PARANUM>26</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab E.</P1></P>
<P>13. The Plaintiffs submit that the language of Rule 6.1.01 is clear. By the deliberate inclusion of the condition <EM>with the consent of the parties</EM>, the legislature intended this as a requirement and limitation of the Court's jurisdiction.</P>
<P>14. Since Rule 6.1.01 came into effect, there has been divided authority on whether a court has jurisdiction to bifurcate a non-jury trial on the issues of liability and damages absent consent of the parties.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>City of Hamilton v Attorney General et al.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 1043</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab F.</P1></P>
<P>15. The most significant decision that found the Court has jurisdiction is <CASEREF><SOC>Soulliere (Litigation guardian of) v Robitaille Estate</SOC></CASEREF>. Justice Smith held that the wording of Rule 6.1.01 did not remove the inherent jurisdiction of the court to bifurcate a trial, but he declined to do so because the plaintiff was ready for trial and to do so would have caused substantial delay.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Soulliere v Robitaille Estate</SOC><CITE>2013 ONSC 5073</CITE><PARANUM>27&ndash;31</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab G.</P1></P>
<P>16. However, more recent decisions from the Superior Court found that the Court does not have jurisdiction to bifurcate the trial in the absence of consent. In 2015, Justice Molloy reviewed the case law from the Ontario Superior Court and found that all but one judge found no power to order bifurcation in the face of an objection by one of the parties.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael, et al. v Potrebic, et al.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3655</CITE><PARANUM>25&ndash;27</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab H.</P1></P>
<P>17. This was in keeping with the principles set out in the only recent Ontario Court of Appeal decision that considered bifurcation, <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach (Litigation Guardian of) v Kovach</SOC></CASEREF>, although it dealt with pre-2010 <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. The Court of Appeal stated,
<QUOTE><P>The practice in Ontario has long been understood to preclude the bifurcation of trials where a jury notice has been served, in the absence of consent. To reverse that practice, as the appellants seek, would be a major change in the law.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach (Litigation Guardian of) v Kovach</SOC><CITE>2010 ONCA 126</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab D.</P1></P>
<P>18. Subsequently, on appeal from a motion judge's decision, Justice Molloy of the Divisional Court offered the following guidance,
<QUOTE><P>On a plain reading of Rule 6.1.01, <EM>a motion judge has a discretion to order bifurcation, but only if all parties consent</EM>. Even with the consent of the parties, the court is not required to order bifurcation, but without consent he or she has no power to do so. In other words, <EM>the consent of the parties is a pre-condition to the exercise of the discretion</EM>.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>The case law is clear that the inherent jurisdiction of the court can be removed by the legislature by &ldquo;clear and precise language indicating the contrary,&rdquo; The court's inherent jurisdiction and its power conferred by statute can live side by side, but the inherent jurisdiction can never be exercised in a manner that would contravene a statutory provision.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>There is clear authority from the Ontario Court of Appeal that if a Rule of Civil Procedure can be said to &ldquo;occupy the field&rdquo; to which it relates, it will supersede any inherent jurisdiction to the contrary.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>It seems to me that the Court was of the view that the new Rule would take precedence over previous custom with respect to a judge's inherent jurisdiction, and that the clear intent of the Rule was to require consent before any trial could be bifurcated, whether jury or judge alone. The Rule itself makes no distinction between a jury trial and a non-jury trial. <EM>If the effect of the new Rule is that there can be bifurcation of a jury trial, but only on consent of all parties, that effect must apply equally to all trials, whether jury or non-jury</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael, et al. v Potrebic, et al.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3655</CITE><PARANUM>13, 16, 18 and 25</PARANUM></CASEREF> [emphasis added], BOA Tab H.</P1></P>
<P>19. Conversely, if the legislature had intended to create a permissive provision, wherein the consent of the parties was not required, the conditional provision would not have been included.</P>
<P>20. Section 138 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM> specifically mandates the overarching principle that &ldquo;as far as possible, a multiplicity of proceedings shall be avoided&rdquo;.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c. C.43, section 138.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><UNDER>(ii)</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>No overriding provisions or reasons to forego consent requirement</UNDER></TI>
<P>21. In parallel circumstances, where the Court of Appeal had ordered monthly payments, changing the trial judge's award of a lump sum, the Supreme Court of Canada considered whether, in the absence of enabling legislation or the consent of all parties, a court can or should order that a plaintiff forego his traditional right to a lump-sum judgment for a series of periodic payments. The Supreme Court of Canada found that it would be inappropriate for the court to make this order.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Watkins v Olafson</SOC><CITE>[1989] 2 SCR 750</CITE><PAGENUM>at p. 764</PAGENUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab K.</P1></P>
<P>22. In doing so, the Supreme Court of Canada stated that the judiciary is bound to apply the rules of law found in the legislation and in the precedents. In stating the limitations of the court in changing the law, the Supreme Court of Canada provided the following guidance.
<QUOTE><P>The court may not be in the best position to assess the deficiencies of the existing law, much less problems which may be associated with the changes it might make. The court has before it a single case; major changes in the law should be predicated on a wider view of how the rule will operate in the broad generality of cases. Moreover, the court may not be in a position to appreciate fully the economic and policy issues underlying the choice it is asked to make.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>Considerations such as these suggest that major revisions of the law are best left to the legislature. Where the matter is one of a small extension of existing rules to meet the exigencies of a new case and the consequences of the change are readily assessable, judges can and should vary existing principles. <EM>But where the revision is major and its ramifications complex, the court must proceed with great caution</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Watkins v Olafson</SOC><CITE>[1989] 2 SCR 750</CITE></CASEREF> [emphasis added] at pps. 760-761, BOA Tab K.</P1></P>
<P>23. Changes to rules of court procedure are more easily made than changes to the substantive law, since court procedures fall directly within the domain and expertise of the courts, which are in a good position to know what changes are required to make the court system fairer and what the consequences of the changes will be.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Porto Seguro Companhia de Sequros Gerais v Belcan SA</SOC><CITE>[1997] 3 SCR 1278</CITE><PARANUM>26</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab L.</P1></P>
<P>24. Rule 6.1.01 is on its face a procedural provision. The Plaintiffs' right to have their case heard in one hearing is a crucial right of a plaintiff in our court system. By and large, hearing all the evidence and facts of a claim altogether is presumptively the most fair, efficient and least expensive option. Only in exceptional circumstances can and should the Court justify bifurcating the hearing.</P>
<P>25. Justice Wilson found that this was such a circumstance. The Plaintiffs submit that the evidence Justice Wilson relied upon in making her determination was inadequate.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><UNDER>C.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Was Justice Wilson Bound under the Principle of Stare Decisis</UNDER></TI>
<P>26. One of the fundamental principles of our legal system is that prior decisions of higher courts are binding on lower courts of the same jurisdiction. The rule provides certainty and allows the orderly development of the law in incremental steps.</P>
<P>27. Justice Wilson at pars 51 to par 63 of her decision states that the Carter decision applies to this situation. Her Honour is relying on par 61 of the Carter decision which references that &ldquo;(1) where a new legal issue is raised; and (2) where there is a change in the circumstances or evidence that fundamentally shifts the parameters of the debate&rdquo; a court may not be bound by the doctrine of stare decisis.
<P1><BOLD>Ref:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Carter v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2015, SCC 5</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2015] 1 SCR 331</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> at par 44. Tab R</P1></P>
<P>28. In Carter the Supreme Court of Canada was dealing with, among other issues how s.7 of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms was impacted by the criminal code provisions dealing with assisted suicide. The seminal decision had been <CASEREF><SOC>Rodriquez v British Columbia (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>[1993] 3 S.C.R. 519</CITE></CASEREF>. The Carter case was argued in 2015. The Court found it was reasonable for the trial judge to take into account the evolution of the law surrounding s. 7 of the Charter particularly in regard to principle of overbreadth.
<P1><BOLD>Ref:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Carter v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2015, SCC 5</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2015] 1 SCR 331</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> at par 46 Tab R</P1></P>
<P>29. That is not the case here. The Divisional Court decision in Bondy-Raphael dealt with the applicability of R.6.1.01. There was no intervening change in the Rule or approach to the interpretation of R6.1.01. Justice Wilson's reliance on the Carter decision was respectfully misplaced.</P>
<P>30. Justice Wilson determined at par 38 of her reasons that Master Short was &ldquo;bound by the rules of stare decisis to follow the &ldquo;ratio decidendi&rdquo; when a higher court has decided the same or substantially the same issue. Justice Wilson then took a very narrow view of what constitutes the &ldquo;ratio decidendi&rdquo; of the decision in the Bondy-Rafael case.</P>
<P>31. Justice Wilson indicates that in the <CASEREF><SOC>Bedford v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2012 ONCA 186</CITE><PARANUM>57</PARANUM></CASEREF> the Ontario court of Appeal adopted the definition of stare decisis found in Halsbury's Laws of Canada. In fact the court while recognizing the Halsbury definition stated &ldquo;the traditional division between ratio and obiter has become more nuanced. It is now recognized that there is a spectrum of authoritativeness on which the statements of an appellate court may be placed&rdquo;.
<P1><BOLD>Ref:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Bedford v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2012 ONCA</CITE><PARANUM>58</PARANUM></CASEREF> Tab S</P1></P>
<P>32. The court in Bedford indicated that the question to be asked in deciding what constitutes binding obiter and non binding obiter was &ldquo;what did the case decide&rdquo;?
<P1><BOLD>Ref:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Bedford v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2012 ONCA</CITE><PARANUM>59</PARANUM></CASEREF> Tab S</P1></P>
<P>33. In Bondy-Rafael the court stated the central issue &ldquo;is whether the motion judge had any power to order bifurcation with out the consent of all parties&rdquo;? Bondy-Rafael was dealing with the applicability of the new R6.1.01 and the effect it had on previous cases and custom. In doing so the majority determined it was the clear intent of the Rule to require consent of the parties before any trial could be bi-furcated. The Rule makes no distinction between jury or non jury trials.
<P1><BOLD>Ref:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael, et al. v Potrebic, et al.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3655</CITE></CASEREF> BOA Tab H</P1></P>
<P>34. The consideration of the right to bifurcate both jury and non jury cases was a central to the ratio decedendi of the applicability of R6.1.01.</P>
<P>35. In referencing that Carter v Canada (Attorney General) has been applied in the civil context Her Honour notes the OCA decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Black v Owen</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 397</CITE></CASEREF>. This case involved a question of a trust to pay maintenance costs and taxes. On appeal from Justice Wilson's decision the OCA held the Appeal Judge erred in law by failing t follow the majority opinion in Amberwood and she was not entitled to adopt the minority opinion as reflecting current Ontario law.
<P1><BOLD>Ref:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Black v Owen</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 397</CITE><PARANUM>37</PARANUM></CASEREF> Tab T</P1></P>
<P>36. In <CASEREF><SOC>Black v Owen</SOC></CASEREF> the court appears to caution against the ready applicability of the Carter line of cases. In discussing these cases the court stated &ldquo;First, unlike Bedford and Carter this is not a case involving s.7 of the Charter of Rights and Freedoms. Second, no new legal issue concerning the positive covenants rule or the possible exceptions to that rule, that were not addressed in Amberwood, was raised in this case. Third, no significant post Amberwood developments in the law of Ontario had occurred.
<P1><BOLD>Ref:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Black v Owen</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 397</CITE><PARANUM>45</PARANUM></CASEREF> Tab T</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>In the Alternative Justice Wilson's Application of R6.1.01 was incorrect</TI>
<P>37. If this Honourable Court upholds Justice Wilson's interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 and finds that she did have jurisdiction to order bifurcation, the Plaintiffs submit that these were not appropriate circumstances to do so because of the inadequate evidence and high threshold for ordering bifurcation.</P>
<BLOCK4><N><UNDER>(i)</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Inadequate evidence to find that bifurcation was appropriate</UNDER></TI>
<P>38. Justice Wilson states at paragraph 18 of her decision that no challenge was made before the Master as to the adequacy of the evidence. This is simply wrong. The admissibility of the evidence was not challenged but a good deal of argument in front of Master Short did deal with the adequacy of the evidence.</P>
<P>39. In obiter comments in <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach (Litigation Guardian of) v Kovach</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal noted that, practically speaking, it would be impossible for a judge at the motion stage to accurately predict whether or not there would be overlapping evidence in relation to the issues of both liability and damages.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Kovach (Litigation Guardian of) v Kovach</SOC><CITE>2010 ONCA 126</CITE><PARANUM>38</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab D.</P1></P>
<P>40. This is clearly one of the reasons that Rule 6.1.01 requires the parties' consent to bifurcate the hearing. The parties are in the best position to assess the evidence and determine what is best for their case.</P>
<P>41. Even at first instance Master Short acknowledged these limitations of a motions judge in his reasons at paragraph 41. However, he continued to make findings regarding the potential evidence and arguments of counsel, projecting years into the future. At paragraph 59 of his reasons, Master Short stated:
<QUOTE><P>In my assessment, the witnesses in the two portions of the proceeding are almost entirely different. The issue of damages will require a complex and lengthy trial that can <EM>easily be severed from the issue of liability</EM>, and as a consequence, the parties will all benefit from the potential savings of time and cost entailed in trying the liability issue first [emphasis added].</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>42. Not only was Master Short unable to sufficiently grasp the evidence and issues of the action in order to make this decision at this stage of the action as a result of his role at that time in the proceedings, but he also made this decision based on inadequate evidence.</P>
<P>43. The <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> provide the following guidance with respect to affidavit evidence:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>4.06</N><SSEC><N>(2)</N><SSECP>An affidavit shall be confined to the statement of facts within the personal knowledge of the deponent or to other evidence that the deponent could give if testifying as a witness in court, except where these rules provide otherwise.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC>
<SEC><N>39.1</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>Evidence on a motion or application may be given by affidavit unless a statute or these rules provide otherwise.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC>
<SEC><N>39.01</N><SSEC><N>(4)</N><SSECP>An affidavit for use on a motion may contain statements of the deponent's information and belief, <EM>if the source of the information and the fact of the belief are specified in the affidavit</EM>.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990, Reg 194 rules 4.06(2), 31.01(1), and 39.01(4).</P1></P>
<P>44. Generally, an affidavit should not contain hearsay, except as allowed by Rule 39.01(4). In order to include hearsay, an affidavit must specify its source and the fact of the belief. An affidavit should contain facts explaining the role of the deponent in the proceeding and how he or she came to be in possession of information that is contained in the affidavit, so that a judge can assess the veracity of the information and distinguish a deponent's personal information from information received from others.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Csak v Mokos</SOC><YEAR>1995</YEAR><CITE>18 RFL (4th) 161</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Master</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; reversed in part (1996), 2 CPC (4th) 385 (Ont. Gen Div) at pps. 5, 7, and 8, BOA Tab M.</P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Lockridge v Director, Ministry of the Environment</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 231</CITE><PARANUM>109-110</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab N.</P1></P>
<P>45. Essentially, it must be possible to test an allegation through cross-examination. Otherwise, there is an incentive to swell the evidence freely with unsupported statements by persons not clearly identified and, therefore, safe from inquisition.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Li Santi v Li Santi</SOC><YEAR>1990</YEAR><CITE>24 RFL (3d) 174</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont Fam Ct</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at p. 3 5, BOA Tab O.</P1></P>
<P>46. Several affidavits were sworn by persons at the Defence counsel's office in support of their cross-motion. These affidavits purported to provide evidence as to the age and health of the proposed liability witnesses: Lorna Ritchie, a Property Manager of the Defendant, and the two superintendants at the time of the accident, John and Sandra Lublinkhof.</P>
<P>47. Tatiana Sanderson, a law clerk at Defence counsel's office, swore an affidavit on May 6, 2017 in support of the cross-motion. She advised the following at paragraphs 2&ndash;4.
<QUOTE><P>Ms. Ritchie testified on behalf of the Defendant in November 2015. At that time, she indicated that she was 59 years old. She is presently 61 years old.</P>
<P>Based on my review of my file, I can advise that John Lublinkhof, who retired from the Corporation in 2012, was born on [date omitted] He is currently 69 years old.</P>
<P>Based on my review of my file, I can advise that Sandra Lublinkhof was born on [date omitted] She is currently 68 years old.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><EM>Attached hereto and referred to as Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; is a copy of the Affidavit of Tatiana Sanderson, sworn May 6, 2017</EM>.</P>
<P>48. There were no supporting documents enclosed or even referred to in Ms. Sanderson's affidavit.</P>
<P>49. David Boghosian, the managing partner at Defence counsel's office, also swore an Affidavit in support of the Defendant's cross motion on May 2, 2017. This affidavit included double hearsay and speculative statements at paragraphs 9,21 and 22:
<QUOTE><P>Lorna Ritchie testified on behalf of the Defendant. At her Examination, at which i was present, she testified that ... Mr. and Mrs. Lublinkhof are elderly. Despite our asking, Mr. Lublinkhof has declined to disclose any aspect of his current health circumstances.</P>
<P>I am advised by Ms. Ritchie and do verily believe that Mr. Lublinkhof is an elderly gentlemen <EM>who was in poor health when she last saw him</EM>. Given his age and the uncertainty of his health, it would be prejudicial to the Defendant if this action is not set down for trial and the liability portion of the action tried as soon as possible.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>Even if Mr. Lublinkhof's heath [<EM>sic</EM>] does not significantly impair his ability to testify at trial, <EM>it is very likely</EM> that his recollection of the events that transpired in 2010, including the interactions that he had with the Plaintiffs, will be <EM>substantially eroded by 2022</EM> or a year or even more, which is the earliest that the trial would likely be scheduled if the action was not set down until March 21, 2022.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><EM>Attached hereto and marked as Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo; is a copy of the Affidavit of David Boghosian, sworn May 2, 2017</EM> [emphasis added].
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Elder v Klukach</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 677</CITE><PARANUM>12&ndash;15</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab P.</P1></P>
<P>50. Master Short and Justice Wilson relied on these affidavits to determine that the delay in hearing evidence from the elderly witnesses was not reasonable and the likely content of these witnesses' evidence, which was key to a finding that liability and damages could be heard separately.</P>
<P>51. At the motion in front of Master Short, the Plaintiffs did not seek to have this evidence struck. However, given the apparent shortcomings in the evidence and Master Short's own acknowledgement of his limitations at this stage of the proceedings in determining the evidence, it was inappropriate for Master Short and Justice Wilson to rely on this improper evidence.</P>
<P>52. The Plaintiffs submit that, at the very least, less weight should have been accorded by Justice Wilson to this improper evidence, particularly where such a high threshold to order bifurcation is clearly required.</P>
<P>53. In his reasons at paragraph 76, Master Short acknowledged that there has not been an inordinate or inexcusable delay caused by the Plaintiffs. Rather, the Plaintiffs have moved this matter forward appropriately. He found, however, and Justice Wilson accepted that the Defendant had established prejudice relating to the aging of the Defendants fact witnesses by relying on the improper affidavits sworn by Ms. Sanderson and Mr. Boghosian.</P>
<P>54. Pursuant to Rule 36.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, the evidence of a non-party witness may be taken in advance of trial. Master Short found that this would not be appropriate at this stage of the action, but offered no reasons for this finding. Examination under oath prior to the trial remains a possibility at this time.</P>
<P>55. The fact that an examination under oath pursuant to Rule 36.01 is even a possibility is because the Plaintiffs brought the action while [G.] is still a minor. [G.] was born on [date omitted] This accident occurred when he was four years old. Pursuant to section 6 of the <EM>Limitations Act</EM>, 2002, [G.]could have delayed filing the Statement of Claim until just prior to his [date omitted]: two years after his [date omitted]birthday.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>, SO 2002, c. 24, Sched. B, section 6.</P1></P>
<P>56. In contemplating dismissals for delay pursuant to Rule 24.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, wide latitude has been permitted as long as the delay is not intentional and contumelious or there is such prejudice from the delay that there is a substantial risk a fair trial might not now be possible.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ref:</EM></BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Woodheath Developments Ltd. v Goldman</SOC><CITE>[2001] 56 OR (3d) 658</CITE><PARANUM>15 and 29</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA Tab Q.</P1></P>
<P>57. In his reasons at paragraphs 76 and 77, Master Short acknowledged that,
<QUOTE><P>The Defendant has not proffered any evidence to suggest the Plaintiffs have caused any undue delay, such that there is no presumption of any prejudice whatsoever to the Defendant.</P>
<P>The only prejudice established relates to the aging of the Defendants fact witnesses which is being addressed by my granting of bifurcation.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>58. These comments clearly indicate Master Short's reliance on the Defendant's evidence regarding the age and health of the Lublinkhofs. The Plaintiffs submit that Master Short failed to provide satisfactory reasons for relying on the Defendant's evidence to find prejudice and for finding that Rule 36.01 was not appropriate at this stage of the action. This was evidence that should not have been relied on by Justice Wilson.</P>
<P>59. The defendant's evidence is that the parties have gathered all the necessary evidence required to deal with the issues of liability. In Mr. Boghosian's Affidavit he swears that:
<ITEM><P>the parties have gathered all the necessary evidence required to deal with the issues of liability including</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>a complete unredacted file of Durham Regional Police Service</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>the Corporation of the Township of Uxbridge records relating to a property standards investigation</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Durham Region Non-Profit Housing Corporation inspection and repair records pertaining to the Unit; and</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>the Lease Agreement between the Defendant and Jessica Knight</P></ITEM>
<P1><BOLD>Ref:</BOLD> Affidavit of David Boghosian sworn May 2, 2017</P1></P>
<P>60. In his Affidavit Mr. Boghosian further swears the defendants have two expert witnesses. Lay witnesses will be Mr. John Lublinkhof and Ms. Sandra Lublinkhof who were the superintendents of the building. Mr. Boghosian's Affidavit indicates that Mr. Lublinkhof carried out various repairs and maintenance to the building. There is no evidence as to Sandra Lublinkhof's necessity as a witness.
<P1><BOLD>Ref:</BOLD> Affidavit of David Boghosian sworn May 2, 2017 at par 20</P1></P>
<P>61. If Mr. Lublinkhof is called to give evidence about maintenance and repairs he will be reliant on the documentary evidence which by the defendants admission has been assembled.</P>
<P>62. If there is such prejudice, which the Plaintiffs deny, then examination under oath prior to the trial under Rule 36.01 satisfies each parties' evidential rights without infringing on any rights. Here, bifurcation infringes on the Plaintiffs' right to one hearing of all the issues. In balancing these two options, the Plaintiffs submit that Rule 36.01 satisfies the requirements of Rule 1.04(1) for the just, most expeditious and least expensive determination.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><UNDER>(ii)</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>High threshold to justify bifurcation was not met in these circumstances</UNDER></TI>
<P>63. According to Master Short's reasons at paragraph 68, bifurcation can only be ordered in &ldquo;exceptional cases&rdquo;. The evidence filed by the moving party in support of bifurcation must be extraordinary, particularly where the other party objects as set out at paragraphs 72&ndash;74 of his reasons.</P>
<P>64. Where the evidence is of little probative value, the Plaintiffs submit this high threshold cannot be considered satisfied. Given the shortcomings of the evidence relied upon and identified above, the Plaintiffs submit that the evidence filed falls far short of &ldquo;extraordinary&rdquo;.</P>
<P>65. Master Short stated at paragraph 71 of his reasons,
<QUOTE><P>I believe there is a reasonable chance that the result of a separate trial on liability will put an end to the action or facilitate the resolution of the damages claims.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>66. More than a &ldquo;reasonable chance&rdquo; is required to justify an opposed order for bifurcation.</P>
<P>67. Justice Wilson in relying on Master Short's reasons erred in finding that the Defendant's evidence satisfied the high threshold to order bifurcation, particularly where the Plaintiffs did not consent.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV"><UNDER>PART IV: CONCLUSION</UNDER></TI>
<P>68. The Plaintiffs submit that these are appropriate circumstances to reverse Master Short's order bifurcating the liability and damages of this action on the basis that Master Short made an error in his interpretation of Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> and he did not have jurisdiction to make this order.</P>
<P>69. In the alternative, the Plaintiffs submit that, if this Honourable Court accepts Master Short's interpretation of Rule 6.1.01, Master Short erred in finding that there was sufficient evidence to determine whether bifurcation was appropriate and in finding that the Defendant satisfied the high threshold to justify bifurcation.</P>
<P>70. The Plaintiffs also request costs of this motion on a partial indemnity basis fixed and payable by the Defendant.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED THIS 11th day of May, 2018</P>
<P>&ellip35; <BOLD>Thomas J. Hanrahan</BOLD></P>
<P>Lawyer for the Plaintiffs</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
