<BLOCK0><TI>FACTUM OF THE DEFENDANT/RESPONDENT</TI>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;NATURE OF THE APPEAL</TI>
<P>1. The Appellants seek leave to appeal the decision of Justice Wilson dated April 4, 2018 wherein she upheld the decision of Master Short released on August 25, 2017. Master Short granted, <EM>inter alia</EM>, the Respondent's motion to bifurcate the trial on the issues of liability and damages.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;OVERVIEW STATEMENT</TI>
<P>2. On May 8, 2017, Master Short heard two motions brought by the parties&mdash;the Appellants' to extend the time to set the within action down for trial to March 31, 2020 and the Respondent's motion to bifurcate of the trial on the issues of liability and damages.</P>
<P>3. Master Short granted both motions and ordered that the severed liability portion of the action would have to be set down by June 30, 2018; failing which, that aspect of his order would lapse.</P>
<P>4. The Appellants appealed Master Short order granting bifurcation. That appeal was heard by Justice Wilson on February 26, 2018. Justice Wilson dismissed the appeal finding that Rule 6.1.01 did not displace the court's common law inherent discretion to order bifurcation of non-jury trials. Further, she found that the obiter analysis of this court in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3655</CITE></CASEREF> was not binding as the issues in that case dealt with the request for bifurcation, without the consent of the parties, of a jury trial.</P>
<P>5. Both Master Short and Justice Wilson correctly interpreted the jurisprudence on Rule 6.1.01, which came into effect after the 2010 amendments to the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. Rule 6.1.01 was not intended to eliminate the long standing common law jurisdiction of the court to order bifurcation of judge-alone trials. The Rule change was only intended to affect jury trials.</P>
<P>6. The Appellants have failed to establish why leave to appeal Justice Wilson's order should be granted.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;THE FACTS</TI>
<P>7. This action arises from injuries sustained by the Plaintiff/Appellant, [G. D.], a minor, who fell from the rear second floor balcony of his mother's residence at [location omitted] [location omitted](hereinafter, the &ldquo;Unit&rdquo;) on September 12, 2010 when he was four years old. At the time of the fall, [G.] was unsupervised.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 44, para. 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>8. While [G.]'s mother, Jessica Knight was attending to a visitor, [G.] climbed onto a chair on the balcony, climbed over the railing and fell 10&ndash;15 feet, striking the top of a barbeque unit and then the patio of the neighbouring unit.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 44, para. 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>9. At the material time, Ms. Knight leased the Unit from the Respondent.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 45, para. 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>10. It is alleged that the Respondent failed to install a functioning lock on the screen door to the balcony in the Unit and failed to keep the balcony, including its railing, safe for those using it.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 45, para. 5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>11. The Examinations for Discovery took place on October 29, 2015 and February 22, 2016.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 45, para. 8.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>12. Lorna Ritchie testified on behalf of the Respondent. At her Examination, Ms. Ritchie testified that:
<ITEM><P>At the time of the fall, she was a Property Manager with the Respondent.</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>She managed [location omitted]in 2010 and had two superintendents, John and Sandra Lublinkhof.</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Both Mr. and Mrs. Lublinkhof retired from the Corporation in 2012 and thereafter moved to Sudbury, Ontario (where they continue to reside). Mr. and Mrs. Lublinkhof are elderly. Mr. Lublinkhof has declined to disclose any aspect of his current health circumstances.</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>She has also since retired.</P></ITEM>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 45, para. 9.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. Ms. Ritchie testified that she conducted the move-in inspection of the Unit with Jessica Knight in August 2008 and that the only deficiency advised by Ms. Knight at that time was a malfunctioning closet door in the master bedroom and bolts that required tightening on the balcony. A few weeks after that inspection, Mr. Lublinkhof changed the lag bolts on the balcony to appease Ms. Knight even though he did not find that they were in fact loose.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 45, para. 10.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. During the Discovery of the Appellant Jessica Knight, she stated that:
<ITEM><P>She moved into the Unit on August 1, 2008;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>She was present during the move-in inspection and she signed off on the acceptability of the Unit;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>In August 2008, she requested repairs to the balcony and sliding glass door in the Unit and John Lublinkhof undertook those repairs;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The Unit was inspected annually by the Respondent and she did not complain about the condition of the balcony or the sliding door, whether glass or screen, during the 2009 or 2010 inspections;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>[G.] frequently climbed on things like furniture before the fall, including, on an occasion a few weeks before the fall, when he pulled up a chair to the refrigerator and climbed on top of the refrigerator. In another incident, which happened approximately 18 months earlier, [G.] climbed on a chair onto the counter in the bathroom, stood on it, took out a Tylenol #3 bottle stored in the cabinet above the sink which was not properly closed and ingested some Tylenol #3;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>[G.] had a lack of safety awareness prior to the fall; ad</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>[G.] has no memory of the circumstances surrounding the fall (and, as such, will not need to testify at the liability portion of the trial).</P></ITEM>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 46, para. 11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. The parties have gathered all the necessary evidence required to deal with the issue of liability including the following records:
<P1>(a) Complete unredacted file of Durham Regional Police Services;</P1>
<P1>(b) The Corporation of the Township of Uxbridge records relating to a property standards investigation;</P1>
<P1>(c) Durham Region Non-Profit Housing Corporation inspection and repair records pertaining to the Unit; and</P1>
<P1>(d) Lease Agreement between the Respondent and Jessica Knight.
<P2><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 47, para. 12.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>16. Expert reports on liability have already been exchanged. The Appellants have retained Walters Forensic, whose liability report was served on the Respondent on June 4, 2015, to opine on whether the state of repair of the sliding glass door and balcony met the requirements of the applicable laws and bylaws.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 47, para. 13 and 16.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. The Respondent retained Nancy Reynolds and Orr Brown Consulting Engineers to provide expert opinions with respect to liability.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 47, para. 13.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. Nancy Reynolds, an expert in child safety and a certified childproof professional, was retained to opine on whether the locks on both the screen and sliding glass doors were adequate child proofing.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 47, para. 14.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. Ms. Reynold opined that:
<QUOTE><P>It is not reasonable to think that latching mechanisms which come in the screen and glass sliding doors are &ldquo;childproofed.&rdquo; It should never be considered that a child at the age of 4 is not able to open any latch that an adult can open. It is up to parents or caregivers to know that children are not able to understand what is hazardous to their safety. They need to take into account that children's lack of prior experience and therefore curiosity to learn what things do, lead them into experiment with everything around them. To keep children safe, parents need to physically take away the hazard. When this is not possible, then they need to take additional measures to make it difficult for a child have the opportunity access the danger as well as supervise them. While it is not humanly possible to supervise at all times, parents should not rely on a product to stop a child from getting hurt. It is important that parents and caregivers understand that products can assist in deterring children but we cannot predict when a child can defeat a device.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 47, para. 15.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. Orr Brown Consulting Engineers Ltd. (&ldquo;Orr Brown&rdquo;) was retained to opine on building code requirements of exterior sliding screen doors and to comment on the report of Walters Forensic Engineering Report dated June 2, 2015.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 48, para. 17.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>24. Orr Brown's report is authored by Alison Orr, a former municipal building inspector, property standards inspector and building code consultant. In Ms. Orr's opinion:
<ITEM><P>The <EM>Ontario Building Code</EM> in effect at the time of the construction of the building, and even the Building Code in effect for new construction today, does not require any locking mechanism on an exterior sliding screen door;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The <EM>Ontario Building Code</EM> does not regulate placement of furniture or objects on a balcony that could facilitate climbing;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The lock on the glass patio door would meet the requirements of the Property Standards by-law, which required all exterior doors to have suitable hardware so as to allow locking or otherwise securing from inside the dwelling unit. The purpose of the lock is to prevent unauthorized entry into the dwelling unit. It is not intended to prevent access of a person onto a balcony; and</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Regarding the condition of the guard, it is notable that requests for repairs were made on September 16, 2009, November 19, 2009, May 3, 2010, and June 3, 2010, and no issues with the balcony guard were raised. A request for repairs was made August 20, 2008, and new lag bolts, washers and nuts were noted to be installed on September 4, 2008. The notch in the top rail would prevent the guard from moving outward.</P></ITEM>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 48, para. 17.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. The Respondent's two key liability witnesses are John and Sandra Lublinkhof, the former superintendents with the Respondent at the time of [G.]'s fall. Mr. Lublinkhof earned out various repairs to the Unit prior to and after [G.]'s fall. His evidence will be central to the determination of liability in this action. The Lublinkhofs currently reside in Sudbury.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 49, paras. 20-21.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>26. Mr. Lublinkhof is an elderly gentleman who is in poor health. Given his age and the uncertainty of his health, it would be prejudicial to the Respondent if the liability portion of the action is not tried as soon as possible.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 49, para. 21.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>27. Moreover, it is common knowledge that memory fades over time. It has already been over 7.5 years since [G]'s fall in September 2010. Even if Mr. Lublinkhof's health does not significantly impair his ability to testify at trial, it is very likely that his recollection of the events that transpired in 2010, including the interactions that he had with the Appellants, will be substantially eroded by 2022 or a year or even more, which is the earliest that the trial would likely be scheduled if the action was not set down until March 31, 2020.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 49, para. 22.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. The Respondent presently intends to call three lay witnesses (John Lublinkhof, Sandra Lublinkhof and Lorna Ritchie) and two experts witnesses (Nancy Reynolds and Alison Orr) at trial dealing with the issue of liability.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 50, para. 25.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. It would be highly prejudicial to the Respondent for the trial judge to receive evidence that may be tainted by severely faded memories which is likely to occur if the parties are forced to wait until 2020 for the action to be set down and an additional 1-2 years before it is actually tried.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 50, para. 28.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>30. A substantial amount of the trial time will be expended on proving damages. Bifurcation of the trial with a trial of liability now and a trial on damages at a later time when the long term effects of his injuries are better known, <EM>if necessary</EM>, will result in a significant savings of time and costs to all the parties and would best serve the overall interests of justice.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 50, para. 23.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. In contrast, it is expected that the Appellants will call medical, rehabilitation specialists and educational witnesses at trial to testify on the issue of damages, particularly how the brain injury which [G.] allegedly sustained as a result of the fall, has and will continue to, impact his life into adulthood, which the Respondent will be required to respond to.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 50, para. 26.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>32. The issues of liability and damages require separate hearings. Further, a determination of liability would significantly enhance the settlement prospects of the action.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of David G. Boghosian, Appeal Record of the Plaintiff, Tab 4, page 50, para. 27.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ISSUES AND LAW</TI>
<P>33. The Respondent submits that the following issues are to be determined on this motion for leave to appeal:
<P1>(a) Have the Appellants met the test for obtaining leave to appeal Justice Wilson's decision?</P1></P>
<P>34. Rule 62.02 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> provides that:
<QUOTE><P>(4) Leave to appeal shall not be granted unless,
<P1>(a) there is a conflicting decision by another judge or court in Ontario or elsewhere on the matter involved in the proposed appeal and it is, in the opinion of the panel hearing the motion, desirable that leave to appeal be granted; or</P1>
<P1>(b) there appears to the panel hearing the motion good reason to doubt the correctness of the order in question and the proposed appeal involves matters of such importance that, in the panel's opinion, leave to appeal should be granted.</P1></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> RRO 1990, Reg 194, r. 62.02(4), Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>35. The wording of Rule 62.02(4)(a) and (b) makes it clear that the legislature's intent was to discourage appeals from an interlocutory order of a judge except in extraordinary circumstances. Leave to appeal from an interlocutory order of a judge is onerous and leave should not be granted where the decision is well-reasoned and the issues raised are not of general importance.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>BellExpressview Ltd. Partnership v. Morgan</SOC><YEAR>2008</YEAR><CITE>67 CPC (6th) 263</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Div Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 2 at para 2.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Silver v. IMAX Corp.</SOC><CITE>2013 ONSC 6751</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 3 at para 32&ndash;34.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The First Test</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>There are no conflicting decisions</TI>
<P>36. The onus is on the Appellants to establish that there is a conflicting decision of another judge or court in Ontario or elsewhere (but not a lower level court) and that it is, in the opinion of the judge hearing this motion, &ldquo;desirable that leave to appeal be granted.&rdquo; A &ldquo;conflicting decision&rdquo; must be with respect to a matter of principle, not merely a situation in which a different result was reached in respect of a particular fact.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Comtrade Petroleum Inc. v. 490300 Ontario Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1992</YEAR><CITE>1992 CanLII 7405</CITE><COURTJUR>ON SC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>7 O.R. (3d) 542</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>55 O.A.C. 316</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>37. The Respondent is not aware of any decision of this Honourable Court where the issue of bifurcation of a judge-along trial, without consent of all the parties, was denied.</P>
<P>38. Much of the Appellants' factum is devoted to the general merits of the case and on this Court's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebric</SOC></CASEREF>, a case in which the factual matrix was different from the case at bar and where the issue to be decided was the bifurcation of a jury trial.</P>
<P>39. The facts in <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> included:
<P1>(a) Two minor Plaintiffs were involved in a motor vehicle accident wherein they sustained catastrophic injuries;</P1>
<P1>(b) The minor Plaintiffs, their mother and brother commenced a claim against the driver of the vehicle that struck them as well as the municipality;</P1>
<P1>(c) A jury notice was filed;</P1>
<P1>(d) The trial was scheduled for eight weeks to commence in Windsor on September 8, 2014;</P1>
<P1>(e) A few months prior to the trial date, the defendants learned of a material change in circumstances relevant to damages and, in particular, future care costs; and</P1>
<P1>(f) The Defendants brought a motion seeking further discovery and medical assessments, which relief was granted by the motion judge. At the same time, they also proposed using the September 8 trial date to deal only with the issue of liability and sought an order bifurcating the trial, so that the damages assessment would proceed subsequent to the determination of liability.</P1></P>
<P>40. The motions judge in <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> granted the defendants request to bifurcate the jury trial without the plaintiff's consent. On appeal, this Honourable Court found that in the face of Rule 6.1.01, bifurcation of a jury trial without the consent of the parties was prohibited.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bondy-Rafael v. Potrebic</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3655</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 5 at para. 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>41. This court's discussion in <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> respecting the application of Rule 6.1.01 to judge-alone cases was not integral to the result or the analysis underlying the determination of the issue before the court in that case, which is whether a motion judge can order the bifurcation of a jury trial without the consent of the parties.</P>
<P>42. The facts and circumstances of this case differ fundamentally from <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> such that Justice Wilson correctly heeded the Supreme Court of Canada's direction in <EM>Carter</EM> that &ldquo;changes in circumstances or evidence that fundamentally shifts the parameters&rdquo; of whether a previous decision of a higher court ought to be restrictively adhered to.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>It is not desirable for leave to be granted</TI>
<P>43. It is not enough for a moving party to demonstrate that two lower courts have exercised their discretion to produce different results. It is necessary to demonstrate a difference in the principles chosen as a guide to the exercise of such discretion.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Comtrade v. 490300 Ontario Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1992] O.J. No. 652</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 4 at para 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>44. This motion was first heard before Master Short and then appealed by the Moving Parties and heard by Justice Wilson. The Appellants now seek leave to appeal the decision to Divisional Court after two previous hearings on the issue.</P>
<P>45. It is not desirable to have the same principles applied for a third time in this case by the Divisional Court when these principles have previously been developed, considered and applied by the courts and were correctly applied by Justice Wilson and Master Short in their decisions arising from the appeal and the original hearing of the motion.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The Second Test</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>There is no reason to doubt the correctness of the decision</TI>
<P>46. The test under the Rule 62.02(4)(b) is cumulative, the Appellants must satisfy this Honourable Court that there is good reason to doubt the correctness of Justice Wilson's Order and also that there are matters involving general public importance relevant to the development of the law and the administration of justice, as opposed to merely being of particular importance to these litigants only.</P>
<P>47. It is not necessary that the judge granting leave be satisfied that the decision in question was actually wrong&mdash;the first aspect of the test is satisfied if the judge granting leave finds that the correctness of the order is &ldquo;open to very serious debate&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nazari v. OTIP/RAEO Insurance Co.</SOC><YEAR>2003</YEAR><CITE>2003 CanLII 40868</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>3 C.C.L.I. (4th) 149</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>[2003] O.J. No. 3442</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 6 at para 23.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Oberlander v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><YEAR>2004</YEAR><CITE>O.J. NO. 1574</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 7 at paras. 8-9.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>48. Madam Justice Wilson released her decision after considering a significant volume of materials and extensive submissions from both parties. She reserved judgment on the matter for close to two months and rendered a 75 paragraph, 13 page, single-spaced set of well-reasoned Reasons for Decision.</P>
<P>49. At paragraphs 47 to 53 of Justice Wilson's decision, it is clear that her Honour had considered and applied the legal principles relevant to bifurcation of judge-alone trials in arriving at her conclusion that the discussion in <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> respecting the application of Rule 6.1.01 to judge-alone trials is non-binding obiter dictum and in this regard, she was not bound by it.</P>
<P>50. The Respondent concurs with Justice Wilson's conclusion at paragraph 65 of her decision that the ratio decidendi of <EM>Bondy-Rafael</EM> should be read as applying solely to jury trials.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>The matter must be of general importance</TI>
<P>51. Finally, the Appellants must demonstrate matters of importance that go beyond the interests of the immediate parties and involve questions of general or public importance relevant to the development of the law and the administration of justice.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Rankin v. McLeod, Young, Weir Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1986</YEAR><CITE>1986 CanLII 2749</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>57 O.R. (2d) 569</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>[1986] O.J. No. 2380</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 8 at p. 4.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Greslik v. Ontario Legal Aid Plan</SOC><YEAR>1988</YEAR><CITE>65 O.R. (2d) 110</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>30 O.A.C. 53</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 9 at p. 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>52. The Respondent submits that this case does not meet the threshold of general importance as the determination of whether to bifurcate this trial based on the distinct sets of facts herein will only affect the litigants to this action and not the general public.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>Conclusion</TI>
<P>53. The Respondent submits that the Appellants have not met the test to obtain leave to appeal Justice Wilson's decision upholding Master Short's order bifurcating the trial in this action.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>54. The Respondent respectfully requests that leave to appeal Justice Wilson's decision be denied with costs payable to the Respondent.</P>
